<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 23 日，星期日 16:07:00 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Why Is Tracy Chapman at the Center of a Country-Music Controversy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对卢克·库姆斯 (Luke Combs) 封面《Fast Car》的回应引发了人们对种族与某些新闻报道的相关性的质疑。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/NvcIwotO5wnf0-DH_gOzPfKHO4w=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/tracy_chapman/original.jpg" alt="特雷西·查普曼弹吉他和唱歌的黑白图像。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>托尼·博克/多伦多星报/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><em>欢迎来到辩论。康纳·弗里德斯多夫每周都会收集及时的对话，并征求读者对一个发人深省的问题的回答。随后，他发表了一些深思熟虑的回复。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/up-for-debate">在这里注册时事通讯。</a></em><br><br><strong>本周问题</strong><br><br>如果媒体的目标包括准确地让公民了解过去和现在——无论多么可怕或不舒服——<em>并且</em>避免以不必要的两极分化或本质主义的方式来报道新闻，那么媒体报道种族问题最有建设性的方式是什么？<br><br><i>将您的回复发送至</i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="mailto:conor@theatlantic.com"><i>conor@theatlantic.com</i></a> <i>。</i><i> </i><br><br>值得注意的对话<br><br>1988 年 4 月 6 日，创作型歌手特蕾西·查普曼 (Tracy Chapman) 发行了一张同名专辑，该专辑跻身有史以来最好的首张专辑之列——天哪，最好的专辑——在很大程度上要归功于单曲《Talkin&#39; Bout a Revolution》和《Fast Car》，其中单曲“Talkin&#39; Bout a Revolution”为她赢得了唱片合约。将每首完美的歌词和吉他连复段召唤到您的脑海中，或者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AIOAlaACuv4">立即播放</a>。<br><br>这张专辑及其最热门的单曲有多不可否认？ <em>《特蕾西·查普曼》</em>在发行的前两周内就售出了 100 万张。它在美国<em>Billboard</em> 200 排行榜上名列第一。它已被认证六次以上的白金唱片。它获得了六项格莱美奖提名，其中包括年度专辑奖。查普曼赢得了三项大奖：最佳当代民谣专辑、最佳新人以及凭借《Fast Car》获得的最佳流行女歌手奖。这张专辑为迄今为止默默无闻的创作者赢得了超级巨星的赞誉和财富<em>——而且它从一开始就为他们带来了这些</em>。<br><br><em>特雷西·查普曼 (Tracy Chapman</em> ) 和《Fast Car》在多个国家也飙升至第一名，这证明了音乐的广泛吸引力和永恒性，而时不时地，当新一代发现它时，闪电再次袭来。 2011年，《Fast Car》被英国<em>达人</em>秀报道，在英国单曲榜上排名第四。今年，当乡村歌手卢克·库姆斯（Luke Combs）翻唱这首歌时，它在乡村歌曲作者排行榜上飙升至第一名。不久之后，查普曼本人向<em>公告牌</em>发表了一份声明。 “我从没想过自己会出现在乡村音乐排行榜上，但我很荣幸能在那里，”她说。 “我为卢克和他的成功感到高兴，并感谢新粉丝发现并接受了《Fast Car》。” <em>Billboard</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/luke-combs-fast-car-cover-tracy-chapman-royalties/">报道</a>称，到目前为止，查普曼的封面已为查普曼赢得了大约 50 万美元的出版版税。 <em>《滚石》杂志</em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/tracy-chapman-fast-car-luke-combs-number-one-song-1234781760/">指出</a>，她将成为第一位“在乡村热门歌曲中拥有唯一歌曲创作功劳”的黑人女性。<br><br>进步！<br><br> 《Fast Car》是一首坚韧而令人心碎的歌曲，它在探索贫困、成瘾、希望、失望和向往的同时，挖掘了我们共同的人性——即使是第一千次听到它，人们也会再次想起这么多人现在的处境是多么艰难。然而，这首歌的成功是一个令人感觉良好的故事，讲述了杰出的艺术不断得到认可和丰厚的回报，同时将不同文化、国家和世代的各种人们聚集在一起。<br><br>或者是吗？<br><br> <strong>“快车”故事的问题</strong><br><br>上周，《<em>华盛顿邮报》</em>时尚版记者艾米丽·亚尔（Emily Yahr）发表了一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/13/tracy-chapman-luke-combs-fast-car-cover/">题为</a>“特雷西·查普曼、卢克·库姆斯和对‘快车’的复杂反应”的文章，重点如下：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">对相当多的人来说，[翻唱唱片的成功]值得庆祝，库姆斯作为<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2022/09/22/luke-combs-country-star/?itid=lk_inline_manual_8">该流派的卫冕巨星，</a>连续 16 次获得冠军，旋风般的旅程值得庆祝。但这也引发了一些听众和纳什维尔音乐界的复杂情绪。尽管许多人很高兴看到“Fast Car”重新回到聚光灯下，并让新一代发现查普曼的作品，但事实却笼罩着这样的阴影：作为一名黑人酷儿女性，59 岁的查普曼本人在乡村音乐领域取得这一成就的机会几乎为零。这些数字很惨淡：数据记者扬·迪姆 (Jan Diehm) 和音乐学家贾达·沃森 (Jada Watson) 最近的一项研究<a href="https://pudding.cool/2023/05/country-radio/">报告称</a>，2022 年乡村电台播放的歌曲中只有不到 0.5% 是由有色人种女性和 LGBTQ+ 艺术家创作的。沃森<a href="https://songdata.ca/">之前的研究</a>表明，在过去二十年的大部分时间里，有色人种女性和 LGBTQ+ 艺术家的歌曲基本上被排除在广播播放列表之外。</p>很快，《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》的这篇文章就成为两极分化的主流媒体故事之一，在社交媒体和播客上引发了人们的翻白眼和嘲笑，以及那些认为负面反应是反动的人们的热情辩护。<br><br>以下是 Twitter 对<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的反应示例：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/Noahpinion/status/1680259202743422979?s=20">诺亚史密斯</a>：“人类只是让人们唱一首歌。把每一项娱乐活动都变成一场种族战争，实在是太累人了。”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/varadmehta/status/1680221377507237888?s=20">瓦拉德·梅塔</a>：“这是不连贯的。特雷西·查普曼不是乡村艺术家。所以她当然不会出现在乡村音乐排行榜上。正如每个人都指出的那样，查普曼的原作在流行音乐和主流排行榜上表现出色。这比在国家排行榜上表现出色要好得多。”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/Egypxican/status/1680237778637058048?s=20">纳迪亚·吉尔（Nadia Gill）</a> ：“艺术不应该被情感所占有，这不是要点吗？它可以是通用的。尽管身份差异，黑人女同性恋和白人异性恋可能会感受到相同的深度和故事。如果我们推动这种叙述会怎样？”</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"><a href="https://twitter.com/FreeBlckThought/status/1680071596411592704?s=20">自由黑人思想</a>：“对于一位已经当之无愧的成功黑人 LGBT 女性来说，发生了一件真正伟大的事情， <a href="https://twitter.com/washingtonpost">@washingtonpost</a>所能做的就是谈论如何没有黑人能够在美国取得成功。”</p><strong>进入战局</strong><br><br>我也<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/conor64/status/1680326375545217024?s=20">参与其中</a>，重申了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/08/what-if-left-was-right-race/595777/">一个长期存在的担忧</a>：大多数新闻事件可以用多种方式来构建，在当今的媒体中，许多记者相信他们通过选择以主题的种族身份为中心的框架来促进社会正义。然而，如此频繁地强调种族身份的影响可能会增加种族间的对抗和偏执的他人，因为那些在心理上对差异最不舒服的人每天都在错误和有害的自负中重申，不同种族的人是“其他人”而不是“我们中的一员”。<br><br>我特别担心过分强调种族身份，因为对有威权主义倾向的人进行的政治心理学研究表明，他们认为的“其他人”实际上是相当可塑的；当潜在的独裁者将种族视为不太显着的特征时，社会中的每个人都会受益。但许多进步人士非常反感这种担忧，以至于他们甚至不去研究<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/authoritarian-dynamic/7620B99124ED2DBFC6394444838F455A">支撑这种担忧的研究文献</a>，而是将这种担忧本身视为反动的。社会学家维克多·雷（Victor Ray） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/victorerikray/status/1680636739763748864">回复</a>了我的推文：“反动中间派和保守派组成的派系淡化了种族在美国生活各个角落的重要性，确保传统的等级制度永远不会受到挑战。”<br><br>对于<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>这篇文章的捍卫者来说，这是对乡村音乐中不可否认的酷儿黑人女性匮乏这一事实的及时、重要的审视，对其的批评证实了许多美国人本能地反对对抗种族主义，以至于他们猛烈抨击任何试图揭示种族不平等的人。当然，有些美国人<em>就是</em>这样。<br><br>然而，对我来说，似乎不言而喻的是，由于持续存在的种族不平等，有可能对种族和种族主义谈论得太少；但同样可以肯定的是，由于种族是奴隶主和偏执狂的错误而有害的建构，因此有可能提高其显着性并过分强调它。更重要的是，对左翼身份主义讨论种族的方法的所有批评背后并不可信的是，反射性地不愿面对种族主义，就像这种无情的评估对于那些方法受到批评的进步派来说是很方便的那样。<br><br>在<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的批评者中，包括我在内的许多人也发表并认可了许多强调种族主义和挑战偏执等级制度的新闻工作。为什么<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》的这篇报道会像许多其他有关种族或种族主义的文章那样令人烦恼？这是我尽力解释我的反应——如果您不同意，我希望您能通过电子邮件予以回复。<br><br><strong>使事实符合理论还是理论符合事实？</strong><br><br>此时，你们中的一些人可能会感到惊讶，因为我很高兴阅读有关乡村音乐的专题报道，因为它与种族和性取向相交叉。这段令人担忧的历史的细节是什么？有多少黑人女性和多少 LGBTQ 人士正在努力跻身乡村排行榜？他们的经历有何不同？ 《华盛顿<em>邮报》</em>提到，在 20 世纪初，黑人歌手“被排除在这一流派之外”。如今，黑人女性是否会被流派看门人拒绝？他们是否因为歧视、害怕偏见和/或复杂的商业考虑而被管理者引导到其他地方，或者自我选择退出该类型？如果可以在不同类型的排行榜中进行选择，从声望、影响力或报酬来看，哪些排行榜被业内人士认为是最好的和最差的？乡村音乐的买家和主播在多大程度上消费其他流派的音乐？我对这些问题和其他有趣的问题没有很强的先验知识，并且对<em>任何</em>经过充分论证的结论持开放态度。<br><br>现在，将这篇假设的文章（通过细致入微地整理事实来询问复杂的问题并论证经过深思熟虑的结论）与<em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的主题方法进行对比。其核心是这样一个事实：很少有酷儿黑人女性能在乡村音乐排行榜上取得成功。该故事没有对为什么会出现这种情况进行细致的报道和分析，而是假设《快车》封面在乡村排行榜上的成功告诉我们一些关于代表性不足的重要信息，尽管这一重要的事情从未被精确地阐明，但它与种族主义和酷儿黑人女性在交叉等级制度底部的地位有关。<br><br>在《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》的文章中，一位黑人乡村音乐创作歌手里西·帕尔默（Rissi Palmer）被引用来赞扬特雷西·查普曼（Tracy Chapman）的作品，但我们从未听到任何酷儿或黑人歌曲作者描述他们自己尝试乡村音乐的经历，这些故事可以更好地让我们了解这篇文章的核心主题。相反，我们听到文化观察家的声音，他们分享了他们对卢克·库姆斯的封面据称告诉我们的感受。作者并没有强迫他们参与与他们的观点明显相反的事情。我们没有听到分析师提出复杂或相反的观点。为什么不包括一个认为封面没有问题的声音呢？<br><br>结果是一种片面的分析，引发了很多问题。我认为对《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的强烈反对很大程度上源于这样一个事实：“Fast Car”封面的成功并不恰当地与一个关于缺乏酷儿黑人女性在乡村音乐排行榜上取得成功的故事挂钩。查普曼是一位非常成功的音乐家，她从来都不是乡村歌手，也没有人认为《Fast Car》是一首乡村歌曲。选择“快车”新闻来探索酷儿黑人排斥现象，迫使文章不再讲述乡村音乐中种族和性取向动态的真实故事，而是对身份功能如何<em>感觉</em>进行推测性假设。<br><br>在这里，例子很有用。黑人乡村音乐歌手和歌迷组织 Black Opry 的创始人 Holly G 告诉<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em> ：“一方面，卢克·库姆斯是一位了不起的艺术家，很高兴看到乡村音乐界的某个人受到黑人酷儿女性的影响——这真的很令人兴奋。但与此同时，如果没有白人作为中间人，特雷西·查普曼就不会在业内受到赞誉，因此很难真正沉浸在这种兴奋之中。”但我们是否“知道”查普曼今天出现并尝试在乡村音乐排行榜上推出“Fast Car”的假设不会受到庆祝？我想，就像我们“不知道”如果《Hootie and the Blowfish》的黑人主唱将自己重塑为乡村歌手并翻唱旧标准的“ <em>Wagon Wheel</em> ”时会发生什么一样。 （这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/">一篇</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/"><em>公告牌</em></a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/country/darius-rucker-wagon-wheel-multi-platinum-8551164/">文章，</a>内容是关于达里厄斯·拉克 (Darius Rucker) 造访乡村音乐名人堂并获得一块牌匾，以纪念他的封面八次获得白金奖。）<br><br> <em>《华盛顿邮报</em>》报道的另一部分表达了人们对库姆斯可能盖过查普曼的猜测：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;">非洲未来主义民间艺术家杰克·布朗特 (Jake Blount) 致力于研究音乐史和重新诠释老歌曲，他在推特上<a href="https://twitter.com/forked_queer/status/1668395667058819073">表达了</a>对查普曼“遗产被实时覆盖”的担忧。他想到了 Big Mama Thornton 的《Hound Dog》<a href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/luke-combs-fast-car-concert-staple-hot-100-hit/">如何</a>被埃尔维斯·普雷斯利 (Elvis Presley) 所吞噬，或者孟菲斯·米妮 (Memphis Minnie) 和堪萨斯州乔·麦考伊 (Kansas Joe McCoy) 的《When the Levee Breaks》如何被齐柏林飞艇 (Led Zeppelin) 所掩盖，以及无数其他经常因黑人艺术家的歌曲而受到赞誉的“白人男性天才”原型的例子。</p><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> “当我写这些推文时，人们[回复]对我说，‘哦，任何人都不会忘记特雷西·查普曼，她已经太大了。’” ……我希望这是真的，但我知道以前是如何发生的，”布朗特说。 “我们知道黑人有远见的人创造了令人难以置信的、强大的、有影响力的作品……但这些作品已被遗忘和抹去。这并不是白人艺术家根据他们的音乐创作衍生音乐的恶意，而是社会的运作方式。”</p>这就是“社会的运作方式”吗？充分认识到无数黑人唱片艺术家受到种族主义的忽视，我们的社会长期以来比这复杂<em>得多</em>。举一个相关的例子，惠特尼·休斯顿翻唱的《我将永远爱你》远远盖过了最初的多莉·帕顿乡村版本。有时，我们的社会也是<em>这样</em>运作的。虽然我可以想象未来的情况，白人男子录制的翻唱歌曲会盖过黑人妇女的原创歌曲，但对我来说，显然在这种情况下，库姆斯版本的“Fast Car”将盖过查普曼版本的机会，甚至远远接近成功的可能性几乎为零。<br><br>我还对报纸的附加说明感到震惊：“查普曼没有讨论她的个人生活，但作家爱丽丝·沃克<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.losangelesblade.com/2022/05/01/alice-walker-sets-the-record-straight-in-new-book/">披露了</a>他们发生在 20 世纪 90 年代的关系。”对我来说，这只是强调了这篇文章依赖假设的奇怪之处。那么查普曼所报道的“酷儿身份”会让她在 20 世纪 80 年代乡村音乐界取得成功的机会几乎为零，因为在<em>接下来的十年</em>中的某个时候，一位著名作家会指出她有同性关系？或许！我毫不怀疑酷儿黑人女性在 20 世纪 80 年代的乡村音乐中面临着偏见。但查普曼的性取向当时并没有被讨论。此外，<em>查普曼并没有</em>面临偏见——事实上，她没有经历过任何事情，无论好坏——作为一名<em>乡村音乐</em>唱片艺术家，那么为什么我在《华盛顿<em>邮报》</em>上读到<em>这样</em>的内容呢？如果不去推测过去的压迫，世界上的不公正现象还不够多吗？<br><br><strong>困难的校准</strong><br><br>《<em>华盛顿邮报</em>》文章的作者艾米丽·亚尔（Emily Yahr）因对她论文的误读而感到不公平的悲伤和谩骂，就像文章疯传时经常发生的那样。更重要的是，如何在多民族民主国家中最好地调整种族与新闻报道的相关性这一问题非常难以回答。观点会有所不同，个别情况下的判断也会有所不同，不同的人有权发表自己的意见，而不应该让他们受到毫无建设性的挖苦或诽谤。<br><br>但就此类报道背后的想法而言，它通过谈论种族主义来促进社会正义——强烈反对是该死的，因为谈论种族主义很重要——我有一个问题：在一个唯我主义的新闻消费者的世界里，他们经常在报道<em>任何</em>问题时都会报告疲劳，如果新闻业将种族主义的报道集中在相对重要的现实世界例子上，而不是例如一些乡村球迷担心黑人女性版本的“快车”可能会受到影响，那么这可能是最好的选择被白人男性的封面所掩盖，尽管黑人女性的版本现在仍然更成功？<br><br>归根结底，我并不反对关于种族主义的近距离、令人不安、详细的新闻报道——但我反对关于种族主义的推测性假设，这种假设在理论上会发生，但实际上并没有发生，至少当它们以一位黑人民谣摇滚艺术家在 20 世纪 80 年代美国取得巨大成功的鼓舞人心和令人振奋的历史为背景时，并将她实际的、持续的成功重新定义为一个令人感觉<em>糟糕的</em>故事，讲述她比白人成功得多。特别是考虑到查普曼实际上比那个白人更成功，这些关于特雷西·查普曼的推测情景会减少什么样的种族主义或种族主义者？我们不需要像<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>故事的最后摘录那样构建身份：<br><br><p style="margin-left:.5in;"> Black Opry 的 Holly 表示，现在是库姆斯邀请一位酷儿黑人女性艺术家与他一起巡演或提供支持的好时机：“你利用她的艺术来丰富你的职业生涯，这让你承担起一点回馈社区的责任。”</p><em>根据她自己的说法，抛开这种对查普曼有利的</em>封面的腐蚀性零和特征。在我看来，查普曼，一个独特且才华横溢的人，写了《快车》，而不是黑人社区，或酷儿社区，或包含所有黑人女性艺术家的集体。对我来说，如果库姆斯找到一位酷儿黑人女性并说：“我翻唱了一首与你肤色和性取向相同的人的歌曲；想和我一起巡演吗？”我会欢呼成功的乡村音乐家为使他们的流派多样化而做出的积极努力，但上面引用的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bigthink.com/the-present/racecraft-racism/">赛车手艺</a>与一个不同种族的人在一个受人爱戴的社区中平等的世界是不相容的，而不是“其他人”。与此同时，我很欣赏黑奥普里的霍莉正在努力做她认为的好事，我祝愿她的大部分项目取得成功，尤其是因为我很高兴看到第一位黑人乡村女明星。<br><br><em>这就是今天的全部内容——下周见。</em><br><br><em>感谢您的贡献。我读了你发来的每一封信。提交电子邮件即表示您同意我们在新闻通讯和我们的网站上部分或全部使用该电子邮件。除非您的初始注释中另有要求，否则发布的反馈可能包括作者的全名、城市和州，并且可能会根据长度和清晰度进行编辑。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 14:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Great PowerPoint Panic of 2003]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>二十年前，企业演示软件被称为“理性的终结”。为什么？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/8o43uZBUeyWGPeMdX_NS8ALYxAw=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/powerpoint_version_/original.jpg" alt="带有螺旋圆圈的演示屏幕" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/大西洋月刊；资料来源：盖蒂</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">新媒体技术</span>将使我们变得愚蠢，将所有的人际互动减少为推销。它会腐蚀我们的思想，降低沟通效率，浪费我们的时间。正如一位著名艺术家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://personal.utdallas.edu/~dxt023000/courses/6331/readings/Byrne-Powerpoint.pdf">所说</a>，它的突然兴起并通过商业、政府和教育迅速传播，预示着“理性的终结”，无论好坏。最终，它甚至会因国家电视台现场直播七名美国人的死亡而受到指责。那是 2003 年，美国人对 Microsoft PowerPoint 所带来的改变世界的风险感到惊慌失措。<br><br>苏格拉底曾经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1636/1636-h/1636-h.htm#2H_4_0002">警告说</a>，书面文字会削弱我们的记忆力。文艺复兴时期的博学家康拉德·盖斯纳警告说，印刷机会让我们淹没在“令人困惑和有害的大量书籍中”。此后的几代人都担心其他新技术——广播、电视、视频游戏——会腐蚀我们孩子的大脑。仅在过去的 15 年里，这本杂志就对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2008/07/is-google-making-us-stupid/306868/">谷歌</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2017/09/has-the-smartphone-destroyed-a-generation/534198/">智能手机</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">社交媒体</a>敲响了警钟。其中一些批评似乎已经过时了。其他人则不太好。但其中隐藏着一种最高级别的技术恐慌，这种恐惧如今几乎已被完全遗忘：人们相信 PowerPoint——Office 软件套件中最令人疲惫不堪的成员，催眠会议的通用转喻——可能是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2003/09/ppt2/">邪恶的</a>。<br><br>二十年后，“幻灯片大恐慌”读起来既是一场闹剧，又是一场悲剧。当时，社交媒体时代已经来临：MySpace 和 LinkedIn 刚刚成立，而 Facebook 的推出也只有几个月的时间。但即使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/12/facebook-doomsday-machine/617384/">极化机器</a>运转起来，我们仍然关注<em>要点</em>所带来的生存威胁。我们是否只是错过了目标？或者，尽管今天看起来很荒谬，但我们是在做某件事吗？<br><br> 2003 年 2 月 1 日早上，<span class="smallcaps">距离着陆还有 16 分钟</span>，哥伦比亚号航天飞机在无云的东德克萨斯天空中解体。机上七名宇航员全部遇难。当破碎的航天飞机碎片冲向地球时，在现场电视观众看来，它就像一群流星。<br><br>美国宇航局事故调查委员会的一份报告确定，这场灾难的直接<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.britannica.com/event/Columbia-disaster">原因</a>是一块绝缘泡沫在升空后不久就松动并损坏了航天飞机的左翼。但报告还指出了一个不那么直接、更令人惊讶的罪魁祸首。早在哥伦比亚号尝试重返大气层之前，工程师们就已经知道并不恰当地低估了机翼的损坏情况，但他们分析中的缺陷被隐藏在向美国宇航局官员展示的一系列晦涩难懂、内容过多的计算机演示幻灯片中。报告指出：“很容易理解高级管理人员阅读这张 PowerPoint 幻灯片却没有意识到它解决的是危及生命的情况。”随后继续说道：“董事会认为普遍使用 PowerPoint 简报幻灯片而不是技术论文来说明 NASA 的技术沟通方法存在问题。”<br><br> PowerPoint 当时并不是一项新技术，但它最近已变得无处不在。 1987年，该节目首次发布时，销量为<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=RC_5OCQQJ7YC">4万份</a>。十年后，销量达到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.webcitation.org/6bxj2eryp?url=https://filetea.me/t1sEVBHlotISPCAVUKpeg2F5A">400万张</a>。到 2000 年代初期，PowerPoint 已经占据了演示软件市场 95% 的份额，它对美国人说话和思考方式日益增长的影响已经引起了批评。伊恩·帕克 (Ian Parker) 2001 年在<em>《纽约客》</em>上发表的一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2001/05/28/absolute-powerpoint">专题文章</a>认为，该软件“可以帮助您提出案例，但它也提出自己的案例：关于如何组织信息、组织多少信息、如何看待世界。” “互联网之父”之一温特·瑟夫 (Vint Cerf) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/bboard/q-and-a-fetch-msg?msg_id=0000iF">打趣</a>道，“权力会腐败，而 PowerPoint 绝对会腐败。”<br><br>到 2003 年初， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Death-Powerpoint-Presentation-Audience-Effective/dp/0964888254"><em>“PowerPoint 带来的死亡”</em></a>这个词已经真正进入了流行词汇。耶鲁大学的统计学家爱德华·塔夫特（Edward Tufte）是第一个从字面上理解这一点的人：那年春天，塔夫特发表了一篇猛烈的猛烈抨击，题为<em>《PowerPoint 的认知风格》</em> ，其中包括他对该软件在最近的哥伦比亚灾难中所扮演的角色的分析。它的封面是塔夫特自己设计的政治漫画，展示了一张军队营的照片，它们在布达佩斯市中心的约瑟夫·斯大林的巨型雕像前排成完美的纵队。一名士兵嘴里冒出一个对话气泡：“没有像斯大林的子弹清单那样的子弹清单！”另一个人喊道：“但是为什么要大声朗读每张幻灯片呢？”就连斯大林也会说：“следующий слайд，”他说，“请下一张幻灯片。”<br><br>该小册子的核心论点借鉴了马歇尔·麦克卢汉的观点，即传播媒介影响传播的实质内容，而 PowerPoint 作为媒介具有令人困惑、简化的效果。它不一定会产生含糊、懒惰的表述，但它确实容纳了甚至有时甚至掩盖了它们——这可能会带来致命的后果。这正是塔夫特在哥伦比亚工程师的幻灯片中看到的。 “PP 的认知风格影响了分析，”他在 NASA 调查报告得出非常相似的结论前几个月宣称。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/11/the-gettysburg-address-as-a-powerpoint/281636/">阅读：葛底斯堡演说作为幻灯片</a><br><br>尽管塔夫特的立场很激进，但人们还是认真对待他。当时他已经作为公共知识分子而闻名：他的信息设计一日游课程与其说是巡回演讲，不如说是摇滚之旅。每次会议都有数百人挤进酒店的宴会厅。 “他们来听爱德华·R·塔夫特的演讲，”一位作家当时<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/advocate_1099">评论道</a>，“就像古希腊人听苏格拉底或未来的超验主义者开辟了通向 19 世纪协和的道路一样。”因此，当“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/30/business/the-da-vinci-of-data.html">数据界的达芬奇</a>”决定参与即将被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newspapers.com/image/114249178/">PowerPoint 辩论</a>”的活动时，人们纷纷倾听。<br><br> <em>《连线》杂志</em>2003 年 9 月摘录了他的小册子，标题为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/2003/09/ppt2/">PowerPoint 是邪恶的</a>”。几个月后， <em>《纽约时报》杂志</em>将 Tufte 的评价纳入其年度最有趣、最重要的想法的回顾中，总结为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/14/magazine/2003-the-3rd-annual-year-in-ideas-powerpoint-makes-you-dumb.html">PowerPoint 让你变得愚蠢</a>”。 “也许 PowerPoint 特别适合我们这个混乱的现代时代，”该条目写道，并指出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/09/politics/powell-calls-his-un-speech-a-lasting-blot-on-his-record.html">科林·鲍威尔</a>刚刚<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20031118030817/http:/www.state.gov/documents/organization/17434.pdf">使用该软件</a>向联合国提交了伊拉克大规模杀伤性武器的证据。<br><br>几页上是该杂志令人兴奋的新想法列表中的另一个值得注意的条目： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/14/magazine/2003-the-3rd-annual-year-in-ideas-social-networks.html">社交网络</a>。尽管 PowerPoint 与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/17/magazine/faith-certainty-and-the-presidency-of-george-w-bush.html">现实扭曲</a>和美国人很快称之为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/17/magazine/17FOB-onlanguage-t.html">真实性</a>”的兴起联系在一起，但 Friendster、LinkedIn 和其他此类网络仍然没有定论。文章称，也许通过增强社会联系，他们可以减轻我们“深刻的民族孤独感”。也许他们只会“进一步将生活分裂成不同的领域——线上和线下。”或者也许它们不会那么具有变革性——至少与像 PowerPoint 这样普遍且有影响力的技术相比是这样。<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">Tufte 现年 81 岁</span>，早已退休。根据他的最终统计，“ET 巡回演唱会”已经结束，共有 328,001 名参加者。这些天，他主要从事<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/sculpture">雕塑工作</a>。但他仍然是他自己：他仍然讨厌 PowerPoint。他仍然从称其为“PP”中获得了幼儿园孩子的喜悦。如果您访问 edwardtufte.com，您仍然可以以 14 美元的价格购买海报形式的斯大林漫画。<br><br>五月份，我给塔夫特发了一封电子邮件，询问他对 PowerPoint 的批评是否已经过时了。一如往常，他用专门为我编译的 16 页 PDF 进行了回答，其中包括他的书的摘录以及一些关于这些书的简介。他最终同意通过电话交谈，但我给他的第一个电话转到了语音信箱。 “在这片时间消失的土地上，外星人是不存在的，”他在电影预告片戏剧性的传出信息中咒语道。 “沟通的关键是语音信箱。或者短信。做吧！<em>嘟嘟</em>。<br><br>当我最终到达 ET 时，我问他，经过 20 年的稳定使用，PowerPoint 是否真的让我们变得愚蠢了。 “我不知道，”他说。 “我到过另一个星球。我现在是一名艺术家。”他接着说，从某种意义上说，他是最不该问的人，因为自 2003 年以来，没有人敢向他展示 PowerPoint 演示文稿。他还声称自己没有“记分”，但他知道——并且很感激——最近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.workingbackwards.com/">有消息称</a>，他的工作帮助激励杰夫·贝佐斯禁止亚马逊高级管理人员使用 PowerPoint。<br><br>贝佐斯并不是唯一一个以塔夫特的方式看待事情的人。史蒂夫·乔布斯还禁止在某些公司会议上使用 PowerPoint。 2010 年在北卡罗来纳州举行的一次军事会议上，前国家安全顾问、时任陆军将军的 HR 麦克马斯特 (HR McMaster) 将 PowerPoint 描述为一种内部威胁；他曾在 2005 年袭击伊拉克城市塔尔阿法尔期间禁止使用它。“PowerPoint 让我们变得愚蠢，”詹姆斯·马蒂斯 (James Mattis) 将军在同一次会议上说道。 2011 年，瑞士的一位前软件工程师组建了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.anti-powerpoint-party.com/">反 PowerPoint 党</a>，这是一个（某种意义上）真正致力于对抗幻灯片暴政的政党。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2008/07/is-google-making-us-stupid/306868/">阅读：谷歌让我们变得愚蠢吗？</a><br><br>塔夫特的文章也面临着一些批评。一些人指责他为了提高他的课程出勤率而制造争议。其他人则表示，他犯了一个错误，因为他将该软件与用户的习惯混淆了。 “任何对 PowerPoint 的普遍反对都是愚蠢的，”哈佛大学心理学家史蒂文·平克 (Steven Pinker) 2009 年对<em>《</em><em>华尔街日报》</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204619004574318473921093400">表示</a>。“这就像谴责讲座一样——在糟糕的 PowerPoint 演示出现之前，还有糟糕的有脚本的讲座、无脚本的讲座、幻灯片、粉笔演讲等等。”长期担任麦肯锡商业视觉演示总监的吉恩·泽拉兹尼 (Gene Zelazny) 将塔夫特的论点<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.robertgaskins.com/files/five-experts-dispute-edward-tufte-on-powerpoint-sociable-media-cliff-atkinson.htm">总结</a>为“将司机造成的事故归咎于汽车”。<br><br>这种比较的问题在于，我们的交通系统<em>确实</em>对美国每年发生的 30,000 至 40,000 起车祸死亡负有一定责任，因为它让司机陷入了造成事故的境地。塔夫特告诉我，PowerPoint 也有类似的效果，它会积极促进糟糕的演示。 “这对演讲者来说很方便，”他说，“但对观众和内容来说却很不方便，而且有害。”<br><br>但如果所有这些糟糕的演讲真的导致了广泛的社会弊病，那么证据就很难找到。一些科学家试图对所谓的 PowerPoint 效应进行<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228864609_The_PowerPoint_Presentation_and_Its_Corollaries_How_Genres_Shape_Communicative_Action_in_Organizations">正式</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/20868864">衡量</a>，询问该软件是否真的影响我们处理信息的能力。瑞士圣加仑大学创意与设计教授塞巴斯蒂安·科恩巴赫 (Sebastian Kernbach) 与人合着了多篇综合这些文献的评论。他告诉我，总体而言，研究表明塔夫特的观点部分正确，部分错误。 PowerPoint 似乎并没有让我们变得愚蠢——例如，没有证据表明使用它的人的信息保留率较低或普遍认知能力下降——但它确实强加了一系列关于信息应该如何传达的假设：松散地、以要点的形式，并由演示者向被动听众的观众传达。科恩巴赫说，这些假设甚至重塑了幻灯片时代的物理环境：研讨会桌曾经被配置为圆形，但在 PowerPoint 之后已被弯曲成 U 形以容纳演示者。<br><br>当我与科恩巴赫交谈时，他正在准备向一家大型政府组织的一群员工进行关于视觉思维的不同方法的演讲。他说他计划使用活动挂图，像白板一样在空白幻灯片上画画，甚至可能让观众自己画一些画。但他也准备使用常规的旧 PowerPoint 幻灯片。 Doing so, he told me, would “signal preparation and professionalism” for his audience. The organization was NASA.<br><br> The fact that the American space agency <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/kathrynlueders_lgbtq_vendor_equity_forum_presentation.pptx">still uses</a> PowerPoint should not be surprising. Despite the backlash it inspired in the press, and the bile that it raised in billionaires, and the red alert it caused within the military, the corporate-presentation juggernaut rolls on. The program has more monthly users than ever before, according to Shawn Villaron, Microsoft&#39;s vice president of product for PowerPoint—well into the hundreds of millions. If anything, its use cases have proliferated. During lockdown, people threw <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.elitedaily.com/p/heres-how-to-host-a-powerpoint-party-for-a-creative-get-together-22793116">PowerPoint parties</a> on Zoom. Kids now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/style/kids-who-use-powerpoint-to-ask-for-things.html">make PowerPoint presentations</a> for their parents when they want to get a puppy or quit soccer or attend a Niall Horan meet and greet. If PowerPoint is evil, then evil rules the world.<br><br> O <span class="smallcaps">n its face at least</span> , the idea that PowerPoint makes us stupid looks like a textbook case of misguided technological doomsaying. When I asked Tufte to revisit his critique, he demurred, but later in our conversation I pressed him on the matter more directly: Was it possible that his own critique of a new technology had missed the target, just as so many others had in the past? Were the worries over PowerPoint any different from those about the printing press or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.collisiondetection.net/mt/archives/2010/12/will_the_word_p.php">word processors</a> or—<br><br> He cut in before I could finish the thought. The question, he said with evident exasperation, was impossible to answer. “I don&#39;t do big think, big bullshit,” he told me. “I&#39;m down there in the trenches, right in the act of communication.” By which he meant, I think, that he doesn&#39;t engage in any kind of remotely abstract historical thinking.<br><br> I tried narrowing the question. Today&#39;s concerns about social media bear a certain resemblance to the PowerPoint critique, I said. Both boil down to a worry that new media technologies value form over substance, that they are designed to hold our attention rather than to convey truth, and that they make us stupid. Could it be—was there any chance at all—that Tufte had made the right critique, but of the wrong technology? He wasn&#39;t having it. The comparison between PowerPoint and social media, he said, is “hand-waving and bullshit and opportunism.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/07/social-media-harm-facebook-meta-response/670975/">Read: Yes, social media really is undermining democracy</a><br><br> This dismissal notwithstanding, it&#39;s tempting to entertain counterfactuals and wonder how things might have played out if Tufte and the rest of us had worried about social media back in 2003 instead of presentation software. Perhaps a timely pamphlet on <em>The Cognitive Style of Friendster</em> or a <em>Wired</em> headline asserting that “LinkedIn Is Evil” would have changed the course of history. If the social-media backlash of the past few years had been present from the start, maybe Facebook would never have grown into the behemoth it is now, and the country would never have become so hopelessly divided.<br><br> Or it could be that nothing whatsoever would have changed. No matter what their timing, and regardless of their aptness, concerns about new media rarely seem to make a difference. Objections get steamrolled. The new technology takes over. And years later, when we look back and think, <em>How strange that we were so perturbed</em> , the effects of that technology may well be invisible.<br><br> Did the written word decimate our memory? Did radio shrink our attention span? Did PowerPoint turn us into corporate bureaucrats? If these innovations really did change the way we think, then we&#39;re measuring their effects with an altered mind. Either the critiques were wrong, or they were so right that we can no longer tell the difference.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/power-point-evil-tufte-history/674797/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/power-point-evil-tufte-history/674797/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Women’s World Cup Is About More Than Soccer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A short guide to help you get into the game <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Nj5jJQCcOjuH1JmFzgDZTb_s66I=/0x134:4371x2593/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1160947978/original.jpg" alt="Megan Rapinoe and the U.S. Women's National Team at the 2022 Women's World Cup" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Alex Grimm / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i>This is an edition of</i> The Atlantic <i>Daily, a newsletter that guides you through the biggest stories of the day, helps you discover new ideas, and recommends the best in culture.</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>Sign up for it here.</i></a></small><br><br> The FIFA Women&#39;s World Cup is about more than just soccer. Here&#39;s a guide to getting into the game.<br><br> First, here are three Sunday reads from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/colson-whitehead-crook-manifesto-book-review/674775/">科尔森·怀特海德失去了阴谋。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/">理解<i>芭比</i>电影的令人惊讶的关键</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/good-conversation-skills/674754/">良好交谈的秘诀</a></li><b>A Women&#39;s World Cup Guide</b><br><br> I&#39;m not a crier. I didn&#39;t cry watching <i>The Notebook</i> , and even the saddest episodes of my longtime favorite show, <i>Grey&#39;s Anatomy</i> , usually only leave me slightly welling up. But every time I read or listen to something about a player&#39;s journey to the 2023 Women&#39;s World Cup, I absolutely lose it. I&#39;ve never played a game of soccer, but I&#39;ve been following the women&#39;s game since 2015. There&#39;s something about the journey of these women and these teams that transcends sport.<br><br> This year&#39;s tournament kicked off on Thursday, with New Zealand&#39;s women&#39;s national team securing their first-ever win in a World Cup game in front of a home crowd of more than 42,000—record attendance for a soccer match, men&#39;s or women&#39;s, in the country. Meanwhile, the US Women&#39;s National Team is facing tough competition as it looks for its third consecutive win. They secured a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theathletic.com/4711571/2023/07/21/uswnt-vietnam-sophia-smith-lindsey-horan/">win against Vietnam</a> in their first match on Friday.<br><br> Even if you don&#39;t typically keep up with women&#39;s soccer—or soccer at all—below are three reasons you should pay attention to the games.<br><br><li> <b>Megan Rapinoe&#39;s goodbye:</b> Rapinoe skyrocketed to national attention for a viral clip in which she refused to go to the Trump White House in 2019, but she was taking public stances long before that, including kneeling in solidarity with Colin Kaepernick and helping lead the national team&#39;s fight for equal pay. As my colleague Franklin Foer <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/06/megan-rapinoe-new-muhammad-ali/592867/">wrote in 2019</a> , Rapinoe makes resistance look effortless. Rapinoe, now 38, announced her retirement earlier this month, meaning this World Cup will be your last chance to witness her creative form of play on a global stage.</li><li> <b>Progress on equal pay:</b> Soccer players at the 2023 Women&#39;s World Cup will earn, on average, 25 cents for every dollar earned by men at their World Cup in 2022, according to a new <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/20/football/womens-world-cup-pay-prize-money-spt-intl-dg/index.html">CNN analysis</a> . In 2019, women&#39;s pay was at less than eight cents per dollar. This very incremental progress comes just over a year after the US Soccer Federation and the US Women&#39;s National Team Players Association signed a new collective-bargaining agreement that stipulates the teams will split World Cup prize money from both the men&#39;s and women&#39;s tournaments (a big disparity remains in the prize amount for each World Cup).</li><li> <b>The global growth of the game:</b> Around the world, women&#39;s soccer is gaining an unprecedented level of recognition.<b> </b>Other countries, including England, New Zealand, Brazil, and Australia, have signed equal-pay agreements with their men&#39;s and women&#39;s teams. Meanwhile, the 2022 Women&#39;s Euro was the <a href="https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/0278-15ff73f066e1-c729b5099cbb-1000--365-million-people-watch-women-s-euro-2022/">most watched</a> in that tournament&#39;s history. This World Cup, Australia&#39;s opening match against Ireland was originally booked in a much smaller stadium and had to be moved to a bigger venue that seats more than 80,000 people. The game sold out, again.</li> Below are a few recommendations for what to watch and listen to if you want to further explore the world of women&#39;s soccer.<br><br><b>听</b><br><br><b><i>Snacks</i></b> :<b> </b>This <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/snacks/id1563105123">podcast</a> from Just Women&#39;s Sports is hosted by Lynn Williams, who is making her World Cup debut on the US team this year, and her friend, the former World Cup champion Sam Mewis. In casual conversations, the two women break down happenings in the National Women&#39;s Soccer League and in the game around the world.<br><br> I&#39;d suggest you start with the most recent episode. It features Ali Riley, the American-born captain of the New Zealand women&#39;s national team, who talks about playing host to the World Cup, and discusses how many women&#39;s teams across the globe lack the training and resources provided to the US team.<br><br> <b>Watch</b><br><br> <b><i>Angel City</i></b> :<b> </b>This three-part docuseries, streaming on Max, takes viewers through the founding of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nwslsoccer.com/">National Women&#39;s Soccer League&#39;s</a> first majority-women-owned major professional sports team in the US With its inaugural 2022 season, Angel City FC set out to do things differently, prioritizing community engagement, drawing big crowds, and giving players a cut of ticket sales. The team succeeded in some ways but not in others: They didn&#39;t make the playoffs last year, and after a rocky start to their second season, they fired their coach. The documentary also gives you a look at some of the players you&#39;ll see at the World Cup this year, including Japan&#39;s Jun Endo, Canada&#39;s Vanessa Gilles, and New Zealand&#39;s Ali Riley.<br><br> <b>And, of course, the matches themselves.</b> Here are a few to look out for in the group stage of play:<br><br> USA–Netherlands, (July 26, 9 pm ET), England–Denmark (July 28, 4:30 am ET), France–Brazil (July 29, 6 am ET), Japan–Spain (July 31, 3 am ET)<br><br> In the US, the matches will air on Fox. You can also stream the matches on the Fox Sports App and on YouTube TV. Telemundo and Peacock are providing Spanish-language coverage.<br><br> <b>The Week Ahead</b><br><br><ol type="1"><li> The 11th season of <a href="https://www.hulu.com/series/futurama-85bf4cc1-cd8b-4469-ad87-7289217a0b74"><i>Futurama</i></a> premieres Monday (streaming on Hulu).</li><li> The third book in Richard Russo&#39;s North Bath Trilogy, <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/somebody-s-fool-richard-russo/9780593317891?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Somebody&#39;s Fool</i></a> ,<i> </i>features continued father-son tensions and a dead body in an abandoned hotel (on sale Tuesday).</li><li> <i>Sympathy for the Devil</i> , a psychological thriller starring Nicolas Cage and Joel Kinnaman (in theaters Friday)</li></ol><strong>散文</strong><br><br>Porn Set Women Up From the Start<br><br> <em>By Sophie Gilbert</em><br><br><p> Late last year, when the streaming platform formerly known as HBO Max announced the <a href="https://www.indiewire.com/features/general/minx-canceled-season-2-hbo-max-1234791185/">abrupt cancellation</a> of <i>Minx</i> a week before Season 2 finished filming, the news struck me as grimly ironic. <i>Minx</i> , created by Ellen Rapoport, is a buoyant, &#39;70s-set comedy about the first feminist porn magazine, loosely based on the real-life publications <i>Playgirl</i> and <i>Viva</i> . It&#39;s a sweet, funny, shrewd show that also features plenty of full-frontal male nudity. The effect is hard to categorize; <i>Minx</i> isn&#39;t “raunchy” or “smutty” or “filthy” or even “risqué.” Unlike <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/06/euphoria-hbo-review-zendaya/591955/"><i>Euphoria</i></a><i> </i>or <i>The Idol</i> , it&#39;s not interested in hollow provocation. And the penises that proliferate on-screen aren&#39;t there to titillate, exactly, although a montage in the first episode brings to mind what the French film theorist Jean-Louis Comolli once described as “the frenzy of the visible.” If anything, the show&#39;s insistent focus on male nudity feels impertinent, as though we&#39;re all participating in a ritual desanctification of dicks. The show&#39;s clever inversion of subject and object makes erotica seem faintly absurd: Here are men&#39;s bodies exposed for us to look at. ……</p><p> Sexual representation, for women, particularly straight women, has always been a bind—our desires are often informed by the same chauvinistic terrain we&#39;re trying to transcend. Both <i>Minx</i> and <i>Viva</i> make one thing clear: Men have set the parameters of porn since the beginning.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/porn-feminism-minx-stiffed/674773/">Read the full article.</a><br><br> <strong>More in Culture</strong><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/zoom-video-meeting-wave-goodbye/674776/">体现远程工作生活的姿态</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/russian-state-tv-putin-propaganda/674755/">I watched Russian television for five days straight.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/"><i>Oppenheimer</i> is more than a creation myth about the atomic bomb.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/august-blue-deborah-levy-novel/674740/">Obsessed with the life that could have been</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/ferguson-report-erasure/674660/">Poem: “The Ferguson Report: An Erasure</a> ”</li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/">An unlikely model for male friendship</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">芭比怎么了？</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/mozart-in-motion-book-review-music/674726/">莫扎特魅力持久的秘诀</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/theater-camp-movie-review/674712/">Sympathy for the theater kids</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-movie-asia-chinese-diaspora/674717/">A raunchy comedy&#39;s subtle wisdom</a></li> <b>Catch Up on <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/climate-change-tipping-points/674778/">Climate collapse could happen fast.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/biden-administration-corporate-merger-antitrust-guidelines/674779/">拜登向效率崇拜宣战。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/electric-vehicles-tires-wearing-out-particulates/674750/">EVs are sending toxic tire particles into the water, soil, and air.</a></li> <strong>Photo Album</strong><br><br> Mountainside art in Switzerland, a moon-bound rocket launch in India, and more in our editor&#39;s selection of the week&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-of-the-week-water-festival-death-valley-jumping-devil/674782/">best photos</a> .<br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>US Soccer actually oversees 27 National Teams, including Extended National Teams with adapted rules of play, such as Deaf Soccer, CP (Para) Soccer, and Power Soccer (electric wheelchair) teams. As I mentioned above, I don&#39;t play soccer, but I am a para athlete, and I know firsthand that many para competitors receive a fraction of the attention (and funding) given to able-bodied competitors. Para sports might look different, but it&#39;s athleticism all the same. Some of these extension teams are new, and it will take time for us to fully integrate para athletes into the lexicon of our sporting culture. The first step is knowing they exist; the second is choosing to pay attention.<br><br> — Kate<br><br> <i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu and Kelsey Waite contributed to this newsletter.</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/womens-world-cup-soccer/674802/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/womens-world-cup-soccer/674802/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Liberal Suburbs Have Their Own Border Wall]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Residents of rich blue towns talk about inclusion, but their laws do the opposite. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/uIM3883HZFkQO372hq4ooRe3_DI=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/SuburbHipocracy/original.png" alt="Illustration of picket fence with barbed wire" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Paul Spella / The Atlantic; Sources: Getty; Shutterstock</figcaption></figure> The New York City suburb of Scarsdale, located in Westchester County, New York, is one of the country&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/scarsdale-new-york-east-coast-richest-town-photo-tour-2019-3">wealthiest</a> communities, and its residents are reliably liberal. In 2020,<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/2020-election/results/new-york/">three-quarters</a> of Scarsdale voters cast ballots for Joe Biden over Donald Trump. One can safely presume that few Scarsdale residents are ardent backers of Trump&#39;s wall on the Mexican border. But many of them support a less visible kind of wall, erected by zoning regulations that ban multifamily housing and keep non-wealthy people, many of them people of color, out of their community.<br><br> Across the country, a lot of good white liberals, people who purchase copies of <em>White Fragility</em> and decry the US Supreme Court for ending affirmative action, sleep every night in exclusive suburbs that socially engineer economic (and thereby racial) segregation by government edict. The huge inequalities between upscale municipalities and their poorer neighbors didn&#39;t just happen; they are in large measure the product of laws that are hard to square with the inclusive <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/29/arts/in-this-house-yard-signs.html">In This House, We Believe signs</a> on lawns in many highly educated, deep-blue suburbs.<br><br> In a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/how-zoning-drives-educational-inequality-the-case-of-westchester-county/">new report</a> for The Century Foundation, I contrast Scarsdale with another Westchester County suburb, Port Chester, which is just eight miles away but has remarkably different demographics. Scarsdale&#39;s median household income, in excess of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/scarsdalevillagenewyork/PST045222">$250,000</a> , is nearly three times that of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/portchestervillagenewyork/PST045222">Port Chester</a> , as is the portion of residents with a college degree. And whereas three-quarters of Port Chester&#39;s elementary students qualify for free or reduced-price meals at school, zero percent of Scarsdale&#39;s students do. In Scarsdale, 87 percent of residents are non-Hispanic white or Asian American, whereas 69 percent of Port Chester residents are Black or Hispanic.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/09/black-families-leaving-cities-suburbs/671331/">Jerusalem Demsas: What&#39;s causing black flight?</a><br><br> On the overwhelming majority of Scarsdale&#39;s land, building anything but a single-family home is illegal. According to data collected for the report by New York University&#39;s Furman Center, just 0.2 percent of Scarsdale&#39;s lots have structures classified as two- or three-family homes or apartments. Port Chester, by contrast, allows multifamily housing on about half its land. From 2014 to 2021, 41 percent of the new housing units authorized in Port Chester were for multifamily housing. In Scarsdale, none of the 218 units permitted was for a multifamily home. When multifamily housing is proposed in Scarsdale, residents raise numerous objections, many of them spurious. Some oppose apartments, for example, on the grounds that multifamily housing will result in overcrowded schools, even though data show that school enrollment in the Village of Scarsdale has been declining in recent years.<br><br> Many people seeking a better life for their children would, in fact, relish an opportunity to move to Scarsdale. In interviews I conducted for my new book, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/excluded-how-snob-zoning-nimbyism-and-class-bias-build-the-walls-we-don-t-see-richard-d-kahlenberg/9781541701465?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>Excluded: How Snob Zoning, NIMBYism, and Class Bias Build the Walls We Don&#39;t See</em></a> , low-wage single mothers from across the country repeatedly expressed their desire for better schools for their children.<br><br> And as I note in the Century Foundation report, Scarsdale spent nearly $5,500 more per student than Port Chester did in 2020, and had lower student-to-teacher ratios. In 2019, 32 percent of Port Chester students were performing at grade level in English, compared with 87 percent of students in Scarsdale—a staggering 55-percentage-point gap. In math, 35 percent of Port Chester students performed at grade level, compared with 90 percent of Scarsdale students, also a 55-point gap. When low-income students are given a chance to attend lower-poverty schools, research <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/housing-policy-school-policy-economically-integrative-housing-promotes-academic-success-montgomery-county-maryland/">shows</a> they can cut the achievement gap with their middle-class peers in math by half and in reading by one-third over a five- to seven-year period. They just seldom get the option.<br><br> Television cameras help depict the plight of immigrant families who are turned away at the border, but they don&#39;t capture the way working-class families in places like Port Chester are shut out of higher-opportunity public schools in places like Scarsdale that prohibit the construction of the types of homes that less advantaged families could afford. Although Scarsdale parents may try to reconcile the exclusion with their political liberalism by supporting greater state education spending in places like Port Chester, economic integration of schools <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tcf.org/content/report/bold-agenda-school-integration/">has been found</a> to be far more effective than a “separate but equal” compensatory-spending approach to equity.<br><br> By limiting housing supply, Scarsdale&#39;s zoning laws—and similar rules in other New York City suburbs—also artificially drive up home prices in the metropolitan region. Earlier this year, New York State Governor Kathy Hochul proposed the New York Housing Compact, which would have given downstate municipalities, such as those in Westchester County, a goal of increasing their housing supply by 3 percent every three years. If communities failed to reach those goals, the state would require municipalities to provide applicants for housing permits with a fast-track approval process. In addition, downstate areas would need to rezone for greater housing within a half mile of commuter-railway and subway stations. Currently, in Scarsdale, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wshu.org/long-island-news/2023-02-06/hochul-wants-to-build-hundreds-of-thousands-of-homes-near-train-stations">nearly all of the land</a> near the train station is zoned for large lots containing single-family homes.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/06/zoning-housing-affordability-nimby-parking-houston/661289/">M. Nolan Gray: Cancel zoning</a><br><br> But though yes-in-my-backyard reforms have gained traction in states such as California and Oregon and in cities such as Minneapolis and Charlotte, the liberal New York State legislature deep-sixed a moderate Democratic governor&#39;s housing agenda—with the help of elected officials and civic leaders from affluent liberal suburbs. Amy Paulin, a Scarsdale Democrat, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/29/nyregion/nyc-suburbs-homes-hochul.html">told <em>The New York Times</em></a> that Hochul&#39;s “proposal would change the complexity of our county in a way that doesn&#39;t make sense.” Westchester County&#39;s Andrea Stewart-Cousins, the Democratic leader of the state Senate, meanwhile, rejected Hochul&#39;s plan and called instead for financial incentives to encourage communities to voluntarily permit more housing.<br><br> Wealthy conservative areas also erect barriers to new housing, but liberal areas are typically worse. Writing in 2022, the Brookings Institution researcher Jenny Schuetz <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/books/fixer-upper/">observed</a> that “decades of painstaking research of zoning by economists and urban planners have produced a high degree of consensus on which places in the United States have tight land use regulations, regardless of the method used to measure zoning.” She argues that “overly restrictive zoning is most prevalent and problematic along the West Coast and the Northeast corridor from Washington DC to Boston.” These areas “lean heavily Democratic in national, state and local elections.” And <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0094119010000720">studies</a> that examine the stringency of zoning within states—for example, California—find that the most restrictive zoning is found in the more politically liberal communities.<br><br> In Lexington, Massachusetts, a Boston suburb where the median household income is $203,000 and voters supported Biden over Trump by 81 percent to 17 percent, the walls of exclusion are steep. A developer who wants to build a triplex would need a lot of at least 15,500 feet—more than twice the minimum lot size in neighboring Waltham (median income of $103,000). By three Boston University researchers&#39; count, a builder in Waltham must comply with 17 regulations, whereas in Lexington, a builder faces 34 regulations.<br><br> Of Princeton, New Jersey—whose voters favored Biden over Trump by a six-to-one margin—the political scientist Omar Wasow <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2020/08/01/us/white-liberals-hypocrisy-race-blake/index.html">has acerbically observed</a> , “There are people in the town of Princeton who will have a Black Lives Matter sign on their front lawn and a sign saying &#39;We love our Muslim neighbors,&#39; but oppose changing zoning policies that say you have to have an acre and a half per house.” He continued: “That means, &#39;We love our Muslim neighbors, as long as they&#39;re millionaires.&#39;” (Having a modest number of wealthy neighbors of color may convince privileged white homeowners that the system is just.)<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/05/zoning-laws-nuclear-modern-family-definition/674117/">Read: Where living with friends is technically illegal</a><br><br> Wealthy suburbs can be defeated in their efforts to remain exclusive. In June 2019, Oregon became the first state to enact a virtual <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/737798440/oregon-legislature-votes-to-essentially-ban-single-family-zoning">statewide ban</a> on local single-family zoning ordinances. The reform happened only because rural Republicans, who tend to be skeptical of government land-use regulations (and of liberal elites), joined urban Democrats to defeat affluent suburban interests. In September 2021, a similar coalition in California repeated the feat, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/26/business/california-duplex-senate-bill-9.html">legalizing</a> duplexes statewide and allowing people to subdivide lots, which could mean as many as four homes on what had previously been a single-family lot. Such laws have “opened up entire communities that had been largely walled off,” one housing expert <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/10/08/business/economy/california-housing.html">told the <em>Times</em></a> .<br><br> The passage of such laws is a stunning development in a country where, for decades, NIMBY forces reliably won political fights. It shows that the zoning walls that have endured for so long—and imposed so much damage—are becoming more and more difficult to defend. Posting welcoming slogans on a manicured lawn isn&#39;t enough. If affluent liberal suburbanites believe that other people deserve a shot at improving their lives, the most important thing they can do is allow families of modest means into their towns.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/wealthy-liberal-suburbs-economic-segregation-scarsdale/674792/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/wealthy-liberal-suburbs-economic-segregation-scarsdale/674792/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Oppenheimer Nightmares? You're Not Alone.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The movie is everywhere—including in our subconscious mind. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/308c3dQsvgB1-RbZS1QulpIfo0E=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/nuclear/original.jpg" alt="蘑菇云" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Harold M. Lambert / Getty</figcaption></figure> Seventy-eight years ago, 5:30 in the morning: a blinding flash, a boom, a shock wave, a crater. As the minutes passed, “a multi-colored cloud surged 38,000 feet into the air,” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nps.gov/whsa/learn/historyculture/trinity-site.htm">according to</a> the Air Force Nuclear Weapons Center. July 16, 1945, marked the first deployment of J. Robert Oppenheimer&#39;s humanity-altering creation known as “Gadget.” The resulting mushroom cloud remains one of history&#39;s most iconic images. And yet, the explosion itself is hard for most of us to conceptualize. What I&#39;ve always found most haunting is the countdown to detonation—when the decision has been made but the world has yet to change.<br><br> Those inexorable, ominous seconds were the basis of a nightmare I had recently. It&#39;s an old adage that nobody wants to hear about anyone else&#39;s dreams, but perhaps we can make an exception for nuclear night terrors this summer. Poke around social media right now, and you&#39;ll notice that scores of people are experiencing acute nuclear anxiety. (“Too many Oppenheimer dreams last night 😵‍💫,” reads <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/GroovyDuuvy/status/1682420217878573057">one representative tweet</a> .) My bomb dream happened last Sunday night. I was dead asleep, watching a missile carve an arc across the sky. I awoke just before impact, sweating, heart thumping, fists clenched. I did not get back to sleep.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-review-christopher-nolan/674749/">Read: <i>Oppenheimer</i> is more than a creation myth about the atomic bomb</a><br><br> End-of-the-world anxiety is omnipresent in contemporary American culture. <i>Oppenheimer</i> is poised to be among the biggest films of the year and will likely nab several Academy Award nominations. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/american-prometheus-the-triumph-and-tragedy-of-j-robert-oppenheimer-kai-bird/9780375726262?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>American Prometheus</i></a> , the book that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/books-briefing-kai-bird/674785/">inspired</a> Christopher Nolan&#39;s film, is currently No. 2 on the <i>New York Times</i> best-seller list. In the latest <i>Mission: Impossible</i> installment, Tom Cruise&#39;s on-screen team races to thwart a possible nuclear attack at Abu Dhabi International Airport. Desert bomb tests pop up in the background of Wes Anderson&#39;s pastel dramedy <i>Asteroid City</i> . A ridiculously large bomb that resembles Oppenheimer&#39;s Gadget even rolls through the streets of Rome during a dizzying chase scene in <i>Fast X</i> .<br><br> Fear of the bomb is also in the news in a way that it hasn&#39;t been since the end of the Cold War. Vladimir Putin has repeatedly taunts enemies and boasts about the strength of his nuclear arsenal. Last month, President Joe Biden told reporters that the threat of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/putin-nuclear-weapons-threat-real-biden-warns-rcna90114">Putin using a tactical nuclear weapon is “real.”</a> Just this week, North Korea&#39;s defense minister responded to an American nuclear submarine&#39;s docking in South Korea by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.yahoo.com/north-korea-said-us-latest-073343487.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAISygpyVVj94OE7dlDMuqoEXRaoavf93iApMfABvZk0-s3HdIWlyDIag_Ekd8pxkCNTc2E5E0HYeK-BQ-kL1XvfetRl_QDopY0E2um-J1-BziXNhvzNXjCGTkBBNT4_Fgm5-HqbHJCUFSXUy0T5fVg60bZir4Z0Lb9IQsB_o56wN">saying</a> that the move “may fall under the conditions of the use of nuclear weapons” according to North Korean law.<br><br> In a sense, it&#39;s no wonder nukes are in people&#39;s dreams. After my bomb nightmare left me unsettled for a few days, I reached out to Veronica Tonay, a licensed psychologist and a retired professor at UC Santa Cruz who has studied dreams as part of her work. She told me that although most people don&#39;t dream about politics specifically, “they do tend to dream about things that are very emotionally valent for everyone, like an earthquake, or like  nuclear annihilation.” She invoked a former colleague, the late <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/13/us/f-x-barron-80-studied-science-of-creativity.html">Frank X. Barron</a> , who told her he collected accounts of nuclear-annihilation dreams from patients during the Cold War. As one would expect, Barron&#39;s data found that such dreams were more common when the topic was more prevalent in news coverage. This phenomenon relates to the “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://hub.jhu.edu/magazine/2022/fall/dylan-selterman-dream-researcher/">continuity hypothesis</a> ,” in which our dreams are an extension of what we see and experience in our waking life.<br><br> Though Tonay has yet to see <i>Oppenheimer</i> , she predicted that the film<i> </i>is “going to put right back into the collective unconscious and consciousness of all of us that in fact we could have been destroyed by nuclear warheads for decades now. At any moment. And we have no control over it.” Nolan recently told an interviewer that he doesn&#39;t disagree with a fellow filmmaker&#39;s characterization of his film as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/story/christopher-nolan-oppenheimer-ai-apocalypse/">a horror movie</a> .<br><br> Our country&#39;s obsession with nuclear destruction has ebbed and flowed over the past half century, but it&#39;s never really abated. The overwhelming majority of Americans were not alive when their government chose to drop nuclear bombs on humans. But the fact that such destruction could happen again, and that if it did it, it might involve a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/09/north-korea-bomb-pacific-ocean/540825/">hydrogen bomb</a> , which would be exponentially worse, yields the feeling that this historical episode does not exist safely in our past. Trinity Site—where Oppenheimer&#39;s team conducted that first test just three weeks before America leveled Hiroshima and Nagasaki—is today part of White Sands National Park, in New Mexico. The surrounding area remains an active military testing ground. Twice a year, the Department of Defense opens Trinity to tourists. Right now, a page on the US Army&#39;s website <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://home.army.mil/wsmr/index.php/contact/public-affairs-office/trinity-site-open-house">warns prospective visitors</a> in blaring red that “due to the release of the movie, <i>Oppenheimer</i> in July, we are expecting a larger than normal crowd at the 21 October open house.” (Referring to this as an “open house” is indeed quite weird.) The notice sounds a bit like the fine print on a theme-park ticket: “You may experience wait times of up to two hours getting onto the site. If you are not one of the first 5,000 visitors, you might not get through the gate prior to its closure at 2 pm”<br><br> <i>Oppenheimer</i> is by no means the first time a film about the nuclear bomb became Americans&#39; preoccupation. Stanley Kubrick&#39;s <i>Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb</i> tackled the subject head-on, albeit from a satirical perspective. Understandably, the serious stuff hits harder. On November 20, 1983, an estimated 100 million people tuned in to ABC to watch <i>The Day After</i> , a made-for-TV movie that depicted Soviet nukes destroying Kansas City, among other places. Audiences were instantly traumatized. President Ronald Reagan watched the film a month before its release while at Camp David. That morning, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reaganfoundation.org/ronald-reagan/white-house-diaries/diary-entry-10101983/">he wrote in his diary</a> :<br><br><p> I ran the tape of the movie ABC is running on the air Nov. 20. It&#39;s called “The Day After.” It has Lawrence Kansas wiped out in a nuclear war with Russia. It is powerfully done—all $7 mil. worth. It&#39;s very effective &amp; left me greatly depressed. So far they haven&#39;t sold any of the 25 spot ads scheduled &amp; I can see why. Whether it will be of help to the “anti nukes” or not, I cant say. My own reaction was one of our having to do all we can to have a deterrent &amp; to see there is never a nuclear war. Back to WH</p> In November, when the public broadcast concluded, the ABC News anchor Ted Koppel hosted a roundtable <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PcCLZwU2t34">discussion</a> with Henry Kissenger, Elie Wiesel, William F. Buckley Jr., Carl Sagan, and others about the film. Before the talk began, Koppel sensed the need to reassure the shaken masses: “If you can, take a quick look out the window. It&#39;s all still there.”<br><br> I asked my colleague Tom Nichols, who grew up near a Strategic Air Command bomber base, about his own nuclear-annihilation dreams through the years. “In college and graduate school, I was studying Soviet affairs and strategic issues, and gaining all the detail that added a terrible sense of reality to those dreams,” he said. “I would be deeply skeptical about anyone in my field who says they&#39;ve never had such nightmares.” (Though disturbed by <i>The Day After</i> , he told me that the British equivalent, <i>Threads</i> , was “the one that kept me up all night.”)<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1945/11/einstein-on-the-atomic-bomb/656626/">Read: Einstein on the atomic bomb</a><br><br> What are you supposed to do if all this stuff is keeping you awake, or if you find yourself having nightmares after seeing <i>Oppenheimer</i> ? Tonay, the dream expert, told me that the moment you wake up, it&#39;s important to put yourself in a quiet, safe place. Imagine you&#39;re walking down a stairway, she said. When you reach the bottom, mentally put yourself back into the scariest part of the dream, and then consciously give it a different ending.<br><br> “I really think that one of the most difficult things that&#39;s happening right now culturally is this relentless marketization of doom,” Tonay said with a sigh. “The movies, the apocalyptic films—they&#39;re expressing a great concern that we all have, consciously or unconsciously, that what we&#39;re doing isn&#39;t sustainable, and we&#39;re really in trouble on this planet right now. And those are real concerns. It&#39;s just that they don&#39;t leave a lot of room for a different ending.”<br><br> “I have seen a lot of young people, especially in the last five or six years in particular, who feel absolutely no hope,” she added, “because every image that they have, that they&#39;ve taken into their unconscious, is that the world ends. And it may. But, you know, throughout history, every story that&#39;s been told, we get to the point where we think everything&#39;s going to end—and then something unexpected happens.”<br><br> Nukes may be invading people&#39;s dreams because they are legitimate threats to our survival. Though nuclear anxiety may have seemed to recede in the decades between <i>The Day After</i> and <i>Oppenheimer</i> , the truth is, it&#39;s been there the whole time. After we spoke, Tonay wrote me a follow-up email. “We do live in a world we mostly don&#39;t control; overt and existential threats to our well-being are real; and our apprehension about that is always present to some degree, above or under the surface of our awareness, expressed in our dreams,” she said. “Rather than discounting our dreams, it helps to recognize them as our own, unique, nightly reminder of how we view the world, what feelings we need to acknowledge and express, and actions we might want to take in our waking lives.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 23 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-nuclear-bomb-anxiety-nightmares/674795/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/oppenheimer-movie-nuclear-bomb-anxiety-nightmares/674795/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Song That Made Tony Bennett a Star]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Where many artists downplay their early work, he kept “Because of You,” his first hit, close to his heart. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/sI8L9QcMTpoOOXM2CKGGC_mppAk=/0x0:3000x1688/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_98589457/original.jpg" alt="Tony Bennett performing in the mid-1970s" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> David Redfern / Getty</figcaption></figure> In recent days, Tony Bennett—who died Friday at the age of 96—reportedly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.instagram.com/p/Cu9kr3gumca/">sang one last song</a> while sitting at his piano. It was “Because of You,” his first hit, released in 1951, and the single that propelled him to more than seven decades of fame, fortune, and legend. But it was always more than a stepping stone. Where many artists downplay their early work, Bennett kept “Because of You” close to his heart. There is much to remember Bennett for, from his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/nbcblk/tony-bennett-racism-civil-rights-mlk-rcna95575">civil-rights activism</a> to his stewardship of classic American pop songs. Without “Because of You,” none of it might have happened.<br><br> When Bennett first recorded the song, he was a 24-year-old kid from Queens whose slim discography had yielded little success. He had fought in World War II, participating in the liberation of Nazi concentration camps. As part of the postwar occupying force, he sang in Army bands. His career began in earnest at Columbia Records (then the home of Frank Sinatra), but almost stalled out before it began. He was on the verge of being dropped by the label when, in 1951, the orchestra leader Percy Faith randomly picked “Because of You” out of a pile of sheet music for Bennett to record.<br><br> “Because of You” has an interesting provenance. It was co-written by a Hammerstein—but not Oscar, the lyricist who famously collaborated with Richard Rodgers. Instead, it was written by Oscar&#39;s far less notable uncle, Arthur, along with his creative partner Dudley Wilkinson. At first, the song went nowhere, Hammerstein brand notwithstanding. But Faith&#39;s chance selection changed all that. His advice to Bennett: “Just relax. Use your natural voice and sing the song.” Better counsel was never given. Prior to that, Bennett, by his own admission, had been unsuccessfully trying out an overwrought style. “Then,” he said, “we decided I would just sing honestly and sincerely.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-remembering-tony-bennett/674788/">Photos: Remembering Tony Bennett</a><br><br> Bennett brought an eventful young life—childhood hardship, the horrors of war—to bear on the heartbroken lull of “Because of You.” Faith&#39;s orchestra curls around Bennett&#39;s trembling voice and weightless cadence, informed by the singer&#39;s lifelong adoration of jazz. There&#39;s gravity to it, though. When he sings, “And I can smile because of you,” the subtext is simple but crushing: The object of his love is the only thing that can keep his spirit from collapsing. But the strength of that love is enough.<br><br> In his book <i>The B Side: The Death of Tin Pan Alley and the Rebirth of the Great American Song</i> , Ben Yagoda calls Bennett “the most justly celebrated singer of standards”—yet “Because of You” was virtually unknown, as was Bennett, when he recorded it. That obscurity didn&#39;t last long. The single sold more than a million copies. It floated for weeks from sandwich-shop jukeboxes and sitting-room radios across the country. <i>Because of You</i> became the title of Bennett&#39;s debut album; it set the stage for his rise, and for the resurgence of a mature pop style whose appeal transcended teenybopper fads and reached a more world-weary audience.<br><br> Like many of his contemporaries, including his friend Sinatra, Bennett grudgingly capitulated to the commercial pressures of rock music—but only briefly. As he remarked in his memoir <i>The Good Life</i> , “I thought the world was losing its mind” when rock started conquering the pop charts in the &#39;60s. His two albums from 1970, <i>Tony Sings the Great Hits of Today!</i> and <i>Tony Bennett&#39;s “Something</i> , <i>”</i> were bogged down by half-hearted interpretations of the Beatles and Stevie Wonder. From that low point, he decided to double down on his passion for jazz, even as the jazz world itself was pivoting away from dreamy crooners during the fusion-heavy &#39;70s. Likewise, he never gave up on “Because of You.” It remained a staple of his live sets and a fan favorite, a tender reminder of the delicate power and ageless warmth he possessed even in his youth.<br><br> Later decades grew kinder to Bennett; by the turn of the century, the world had fully embraced him once again. “Because of You” was, in part, responsible for the revival of his popularity; his rendition of this song with kd lang helped make his 2006 album, <i>Duets: An American Classic</i> , a platinum-selling triumph. It also paved the way for the final chapter of Bennett&#39;s decorated career, in which he sang with younger artists such as Amy Winehouse and Lady Gaga, ensuring his resonance for generations to come.<br><br> Bennett might not have realized that “Because of You” would be his swan song, but it couldn&#39;t have served as a better bookend. If by some twist of fate it had been his only hit, it would still echo with ache. As history would have it, though, the song was both the opening of and the epitaph to his career. “Because of You” made Bennett a star—and largely because of him, popular music retains a body of song whose romance will forever make us swoon.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 20:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/tony-bennett-because-of-you/674801/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/tony-bennett-because-of-you/674801/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Wrong-Apartment Problem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>为什么良好的经济感觉如此糟糕<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/P0ehptGO9OM3LXE_iAs36pWlHiY=/0x0:2500x1406/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/Economy_1/original.png" alt="向上箭头上的图形图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·希基插图</figcaption></figure>电台上的《Dr. Dre》、大银幕上的<i>《黑客帝国》</i> 、电视上的<i>《黑道家族</i>》：1999 年因多种原因而精彩，其中也包括经济因素。<br><br>那一年，家庭收入中位数升至创纪录水平，这一水位保持了近二十年。 （唐纳德·特朗普竞选公职时的美国家庭平均水平比比尔·克林顿卸任时还要贫困。）工资全面增长——各种工人都得到了持续的加薪。生产率增长<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/PRS85006092">强劲</a>。财富不平等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/WFRBST01134">保持稳定</a>，并且远<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/WFRBST01134">低于今天</a>。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.povertycenter.columbia.edu/historical-spm-data">贫困率</a>降至多年来的最低点。<br><br>我可以继续不断地提供硬性统计数据：拥有大学学位的工人比例正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/184260/educational-attainment-in-the-us/#:~:text=In%202020%2C%20about%2037.9%20percent,population%20had%20graduated%20from%20college.">攀升</a>。住房拥有率正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/RHORUSQ156N">蓬勃发展</a>。股市，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/index/spx">欣欣向荣</a>。消费者信心达到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tradingeconomics.com/united-states/consumer-confidence#:~:text=Consumer%20Confidence%20in%20the%20United,points%20in%20June%20of%202022.">历史</a>最高水平。就业人数比例创<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/EMRATIO">历史新高</a>。投资者的乐观情绪达到了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/352334/inflation-concerns-temper-investor-optimism.aspx">历史</a>最高水平。认为国家正在朝着正确方向前进的美国人比例也<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/1669/general-mood-country.aspx">达到了</a>历史最高水平。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">亚沙·蒙克：再见末日先知</a><br><br>一切都<i>感觉</i>进展顺利并且正在变得更好。高品质电视变得无处不在。手机开始取代寻呼机。拥有电脑和互联网连接的家庭比例<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2018/acs/ACS-39.pdf">呈爆炸式增长</a>，而网络有望改变一切。<br><br>现在：收音机里充斥着令人耳目一新的 TikTok，大屏幕上的超级英雄让人热血沸腾（至少在<i>巴本海默</i>之前），Peak TV 让我们淹没在还不错的内容中：2023 年由于多种原因而乏味。大约有一半的人认为我们正处于或即将陷入衰退。消费者信心下降，投资者情绪也下降。通货膨胀正在给美国家庭带来压力。<br><br>但我来这里是想告诉你们，这是有史以来最好的经济。真的。今年的经济增速已经超过了 1999 年，这是有记录以来最好的一年。它的增长比多年来更加公平。美国家庭的财务状况比以往任何时候都更加安全和富裕。事情进展顺利，我发誓。<br><br>劳动力市场正在蓬勃发展，而且不仅仅是富人的繁荣。失业率处于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/UNRATE">60 年</a>来的最低水平——就业机会比<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/JTSJOR">一代人以来的任何时候</a>都多。对工人的竞争不仅推高了收入——家庭收入中位数正接近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MEHOINUSA672N">新高</a>，比 20 世纪 90 年代末高出 6,000 美元。它还使收入最低的工人的收入比收入最高的工人的收入增加更多。过去三年消除了过去四十年来工资不平等<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w31010/w31010.pdf">加剧的四分之一</a>。最低收入工人的实际工资增长速度比 20 世纪 60 年代以来还要快。该国的工资结构正在变得更加平等，而不是更加平等。<br><br>研究这一“<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w31010">意外</a>”现象的劳动经济学家阿林德拉吉特·杜贝(Arindrajit Dube)告诉我，这个国家的“职业阶梯”在大约20年前就已经破裂：从事糟糕工作的工人发现自己被困在那些糟糕的工作中，无法晋升。 “从 2018 年或 2019 年左右开始，你开始看到紧张的劳动力市场恢复了一些健康和活力，”他告诉我。 “人们正在做出更多改变。大辞职、大洗牌，无论你怎么称呼它——这都意味着市场正在更好地运转。它允许人们离开非常糟糕的工作。”因此，工人们表示，他们现在对自己的工作感到比 20 世纪 80 年代以来的任何时候<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.conference-board.org/research/job-satisfaction/US-worker-satisfaction-continues-to-increase">都更加满意</a>，而且与大流行之前相比，拥有全职工作的人数增加了 400 万人（ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/juliaonjobs/status/1678747214594678784">从事兼职工作的</a>人数减少了 160 万人）。<br><br>收入的改善，加上政府在疫情期间提供的刺激资金，帮助数百万家庭摆脱了贫困。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2022/demo/p60-277.pdf">过去三年</a>，儿童贫困率从 12.5% 下降到 5.2%。这是有记录以来的最低水平。生活在深度贫困和接近贫困的人口比例<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/content/dam/Census/library/publications/2022/demo/p60-277.pdf">也有所下降</a>，粮食不安全率降至<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/ag-and-food-statistics-charting-the-essentials/food-security-and-nutrition-assistance/#:~:text=In%202021%2C%2089.8%20percent%20of,had%20very%20low%20food%20security.">历史最低水平</a>。<br><br>更高的薪水正在帮助中产阶级家庭购买房屋并积累财富。住房拥有率的增长速度<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nar.realtor/newsroom/u-s-homeownership-rate-experiences-largest-annual-increase-on-record-though-black-homeownership-remains-lower-than-decade-ago">比以往任何时候</a>都快，直到一年前利率飙升；<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/housing/hvs/data/histtabs.html">自 2006 年房地产泡沫</a>破裂以来，处于收入分布下半部分的家庭现在拥有自己住房的可能性比任何时候都大。大多数千禧一代拥有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.apartmentlist.com/research/millennial-homeownership-2023">房产</a>；这一代人在净资产和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jchs.harvard.edu/blog/surge-household-growth-and-what-it-suggests-about-future-housing-demand">家庭构成</a>方面开始赶上X一代和婴儿潮一代。<br><br>经济也为美国黑人带来了非凡的收益。黑人工人的失业率接近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LNS14000006">历史低点</a>，白人工人和黑人工人的失业率<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LNS14000006#0">之间的差距</a>是有史以来最小的。黑人工人的收入也在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LEU0252884600Q">迅速增长</a>。<br><br>以各种更深奥的方式来衡量，美国家庭正在做得最好。贷款拖欠率<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/DRALACBN">达到历史</a>最低水平。实际可支配收入达到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/A229RX0A048NBEA">历史</a>最高水平。个人破产率处于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://finmasters.com/personal-bankruptcy-statistics/#gref">历史最低水平</a>。<br><br>所以我们不得不问：为什么我们不像 1999 年那样狂欢呢？<br><br>最直接的答案是通货膨胀。它不仅消耗了人们的薪水（尽管按通货膨胀调整后的收入和可支配收入仍然上升）。人们只是讨厌每次加满油或去杂货店时都要进行心算。消费者往往不会注意到情况何时变得更好，而不是更糟：通货膨胀已大幅降温，鸡蛋、汽油、二手车、飞机票和数十种其他常见<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.nr0.htm">消费品</a>的价格正在下降，但这一事实尚未渗透到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/1675/most-important-problem.aspx">许多家庭</a>中。<br><br>然后有一个我喜欢称之为错误公寓问题的问题。过去几十年里，中国大城市新增的住房数量太少；现在连农村地区也出现短缺。据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/us-housing-gap-cost-affordability-big-cities/672184/">一项估计</a>，如果供应满足需求，大约一半的美国人会住在不同的地方；纽约将是现在的八倍，旧金山将是现在的五倍。与 1999 年相比，租房者在住房上的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.anderson.ucla.edu/documents/areas/ctr/ziman/ConfAfford2015_Albouy-Ehrlich-Liu_Housing-Demand-Expenditures2_09.09.15.pdf">支出占</a>收入的比例更高，租金<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.moodys.com/web/en/us/about/insights/data-stories/us-rental-housing-affordability.html">增长了</a>135%，而平均收入仅增长了 77%。该国面临<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/great-affordability-crisis-breaking-america/606046/">负担能力危机</a>，医疗保健、儿童保育和房租占据了家庭预算的很大一部分。<br><br>然而这些统计数据仍然<i>低估了</i>情况的严重程度。人们不会花他们买不起的东西，而且几乎没有人再买得起他们想要的东西了。是的，我们比历史上任何时候都拥有更多的收入、更多的可支配现金和更好的生活水平。但我们中有数百万人无法生活在我们想要的社区中。我们被困在太小、太远的住处，放弃了拥有第二间浴室或第三个孩子的梦想。这就是为什么你会在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LifesNotFoehr/status/1676341223349534721">社交媒体上怀念</a>20 世纪 50 年代的经济状况，当时许多美国人仍然缺乏<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/data/tables/time-series/dec/coh-plumbing.html">室内管道</a>，但至少可以以合理的薪水生活在布鲁克林、萨默维尔或旧金山。我们都被困在错误的公寓里了。<br><br>第三个主要因素是不平等。尽管低收入美国人已经开始缩小差距，但这是最近才出现的现象。最富有的人的收入增长速度<i>仍然</i>快于其他人。即使生活水平正在提高，但收益未得到平等分享的感觉对我们的政体来说是有害的。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/bidenomics-economic-pessimism/674701/">詹姆斯·苏罗维茨基（James Surowiecki）：不良氛围经济</a><br><br>政治和媒体环境肯定也是因素。今天强烈的两极分化促使人们如果讨厌总统就讨厌经济，如果喜欢总统就喜欢经济，这意味着共和党人现在不高兴。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://direct.mit.edu/rest/article/105/3/493/100979/Partisan-Bias-Economic-Expectations-and-Household">新的研究发现，</a> “党派偏见对经济预期的调查指标产生重大影响，而且这种偏见正在加剧”。打开电视，世界也变得一片混乱：气候灾难、欧洲战争、国内民主受到威胁、社交媒体烧坏了我们的大脑、破坏了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/12/the-sex-recession/573949/">性</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/culture/2023/02/hanging-out-sheila-liming-book-friendship-crisis.html">闲逛</a>等乐趣。又有什么可高兴的呢？<br><br>对此感到高兴：就经济而言，这一次一切进展顺利。他们很棒。他们和以前一样好。我保证。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/us-economy-labor-market-inflation-housing/674790/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/us-economy-labor-market-inflation-housing/674790/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[How Older People Get Scammed]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我们可以采取什么措施来预防它<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/lvzc2I0FP_6FVmT7NowCt6HQsAM=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/Atlantic_Elder_Scams_Wide_01/original.jpg" alt="一张摇椅被几个钩子拉动的照片插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由泰勒·科姆里 (Tyler Comrie) 绘制。 Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure>当我父亲快九十岁的时候，他邮箱里的信件每天都在增加——有时会收到十几封捐款呼吁。他对自己节俭得令人难以置信：磨损的帆布鞋和破烂的风衣一年四季都穿。他厌恶浪费。当律师打来电话时，他会放下电话。但他的邮箱里充斥着大量的资金恳求，其中包括许多来自消防员、执法部门和退伍军人基金的资金，但通常最终都会出现在他的办公桌上。通常，慷慨会掩盖怀疑，这意味着他会发出很多小额支票。尽管他在 90 多岁的时候告诉我，“我怀疑他们会出售你的信息，然后每个人都会向你要钱。”<br><br>我父亲写的支票对他没有伤害，但知道什么时候可以安全地捐钱并不容易。这只是对老年人的一个重要但被忽视的威胁的一个方面：经济剥削。它可以有多种形式。看似合法的筹款请求可能会导致过度压力。有时现有的关系，例如与会计师的关系，会变得具有掠夺性。家人和朋友也在生活中利用老年人的经济优势。还有一些陌生人设计出彻头彻尾的骗局，冒充慈善机构、亲戚，甚至潜在的浪漫伴侣，对上了年纪的美国人下手。<br><br>我作为一名民事欺诈检察官以及在司法部发起一项旨在保护老年人的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/elderjustice">倡议</a>时认识了这些问题。离开司法部后，我的研究，包括我的书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-measure-of-our-age-navigating-care-safety-money-and-meaning-later-in-life-m-t-connolly/9781541702721"><em>衡量我们的年龄》</em></a> ，向我揭示了老年人在成为金钱目标时可能面临的无形伤害。<br><br>我们不知道问题的全部规模。但我们确实知道，金融剥削的受害者大部分年龄都在 60 岁以上； 70 多岁的人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/data-visualizations/data-spotlight/2022/12/who-experiences-scams-story-all-ages">报告的</a>损失中位数高于年轻人，而 80 岁及以上的人报告的损失中位数最高。对老年人经济剥削每年造成的累计损失金额的估计差异很大，从<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/protecting-older-consumers-2020-2021-report-federal-trade-commission/protecting-older-consumers-report-508.pdf">数亿</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/file/1523276/download">美元</a>到<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://states.aarp.org/colorado/aarp-report-28-3-billion-a-year-stolen-from-adults-60#:~:text=Older%20Americans%20lose%20an%20estimated,report%20these%20incidents%20to%20authorities.">数</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fincen.gov/sites/default/files/advisory/2022-06-15/FinCEN%20Advisory%20Elder%20Financial%20Exploitation%20FINAL%20508.pdf">百亿</a>美元不等。这些数字很难确定，部分原因是 60 岁以上的人举报欺诈的可能性较小。显而易见的是，潜在目标群体正在变得越来越大：85 岁及以上的人是美国人口中增长最快的群体，预计从 2019 年的 660 万增加<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://acl.gov/sites/default/files/aging%20and%20Disability%20In%20America/2020Profileolderamericans.final_.pdf">一倍多，</a>到 2040 年达到 1,440 万。我们的社会还没有做好保护这一不断增长的人口群体免受金融剥削的准备。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/old-age-personality-brain-changes-psychology/674668/">阅读：年老时奇怪的性格变化</a><br><br>被剥削本身显然就是一种不公正。但不太明显的是这些事件对老年人造成伤害的程度和严重性。一些受害者失去了房屋或结婚戒指等贵重物品，或者无法再支付所需的护理费用。有些人畏缩在自己的家中，担心家人会被盗窃或威胁寻求资金来支持毒瘾。经济损失可能会加剧并加速身心健康的下降，使生活从独立转向依赖。<br><br>威尔康奈尔医学院老年病学和姑息医学联席主任马克·拉克斯发现，虐待老年人，包括经济剥削，会使受害者的过早死亡率增加<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/187817">三倍</a>，入住疗养院的人数增加<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/gerontologist/article/42/6/734/671735">四倍</a>。落入骗局，无论年龄多大，都会感到尴尬、绝望和恐惧<em>——我怎么会这么蠢呢？</em> ——并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.finrafoundation.org/sites/finrafoundation/files/non-traditional-costs-financial-fraud.pdf">造成严重的压力</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aarp.org/money/scams-fraud/info-2022/mental-health-impact.html">有时甚至导致自杀</a>。想想游戏后期对像 Jenga 这样的老年人的影响：虽然有些摇晃，但塔仍然矗立着。然后，某个事件拉出了一个关键的块，推翻了结构。<br><br>当老年人的资产被盗时，其他人也会遭受损失。成年子女可能会失去家庭住宅，继承的遗产逐渐减少，或者被迫承担照顾责任。试图保护老年人免受剥削和其他虐待可能会给想要提供帮助的关心的亲戚或朋友带来巨大的痛苦。<br><br>任何人都可能成为经济剥削的受害者，但认知障碍会增加<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/biomedgerontology/article/72/10/1365/3091724?login=false">风险</a>。随着记忆力和执行功能随着年龄的增长而下降， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sifma.org/resources/news/financial-capacity-and-financial-exploitation/">财务能力</a>（例如支付账单或管理资产的能力）也会下降。对于一些人来说，在诊断出痴呆症之前很久，他们的经济能力<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamainternalmedicine/fullarticle/2773241">就已经下降</a>，而这种情况通常未被发现。当有人意外地打电话要钱时，我们的大脑会解析数千条社交线索。事实上，“直觉”是从大脑的前岛叶发出的，它告诉我们<em>这里有些不对劲！</em>信号。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/why-older-adults-are-too-trusting/">衰老会使这些信号变暗</a>，或者完全消失，从而使一些老年人不那么怀疑。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nap.nationalacademies.org/catalog/25663/social-isolation-and-loneliness-in-older-adults-opportunities-for-the">孤立</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/aging/publications/features/lonely-older-adults.html">孤独</a>、美国老年人中的流行病也<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7741502/">加剧了风险</a>。<br><br>最令人震惊的骗局依赖于无数的虚构，而<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/07/21/zients-biden-ai-authority">人工智能</a>和其他技术只会让这些虚构变得更加真实。骗子可能会冒充警察、律师或医院工作人员报告虚假紧急情况以引发恐惧。 “Grandma&#39;ed”已经进入词汇，用来描述人们接到电话帮助一个处于危机中、立即需要现金的所谓孙子。政府报告称，2019 年和 2020 年索要资金解决虚假社会保障相关<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ssa.gov/scam/?gclid=Cj0KCQjwnrmlBhDHARIsADJ5b_lXllU50W31c63vnspiWyDYOrzlxVFS0f-LsmshOVXJY_nOJMqfKSMaAkBVEALw_wcB">问题</a>的诈骗者激增；受害者的年龄越大，损失的钱就越多。 “浪漫”诈骗，也称为“情人”诈骗，是 60 岁及以上老年人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/protecting-older-consumers-2020-2021-report-federal-trade-commission/protecting-older-consumers-report-508.pdf">损失最多</a>的陌生人诈骗类型。许多骗子利用 BigChurch、Christian Mingle 和 Jdate 等宗教交友网站来寻找那些无法想象自己可能会被与其信仰相同的人欺骗的人。<br><br>一些针对老年人的诈骗者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aarp.org/money/scams-fraud/info-2019/veterans-charity.html">冒充</a>慈善组织。但即使是来自真正的、受人尊敬的机构（大学、倡导组织、文化团体、政治实体）的发展专业人士也可能不会停下来考虑潜在捐助者是否有财务能力，以及积极推动他们捐款是否道德或公平。<br><br>还有一些人一开始担任合法角色，但最终成为掠夺者。罗恩·朗 (Ron Long) 是富国银行顾问计划的联合创始人，该计划旨在培训员工发现并应对老年人的剥削行为。他向我讲述了一位美发师的故事，他成为了几位富有客户的授权书和唯一受益人。律师、经纪人——实际上是长辈信任的任何人——都可能走向欺骗。朗说：“只要知道自己的财务和认知状况的人不诚实就可以了。”<br><br>加州大学欧文分校医学院助理副校长雪莉·卡普兰 (Sherrie Kaplan) 向我讲述了她已故的母亲如何在一个房屋维修项目中受到剥削的故事。尽管卡普兰患有心脏病和轻度痴呆症，并且失去了丈夫，但卡普兰的母亲独自生活得很好。然后她的浴缸倒退了。为了不想给孩子增加负担，她从电话簿中挑选了一位水管工。最初的估价为 800 美元，后来飙升至 8,000 多美元。工作也随之增长。突然，男人们开始挖掘她的车道。然后催款电话就来了，工作人员敲门要求付款。她没有告诉孩子们，因为担心他们认为她不能再独自生活了。相反，她因自己被利用而感到害怕和羞愧，因此不再外出，错过了医生的预约，也没有补充她的处方。然后她的心脏衰竭，需要紧急心脏手术。她从未完全康复，不仅失去了金钱，而且很可能失去了生命中的岁月。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/03/older-adults-covid-health-quality-of-life/673507/">阅读：现在老年人的生活更糟</a><br><br>家庭成员可能会给老年人带来一些最大的经济威胁：据估计，剥削年长亲戚的人的盗窃行为平均<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://files.consumerfinance.gov/f/documents/cfpb_suspicious-activity-reports-elder-financial-exploitation_report.pdf">是陌生人的两倍半</a>。在家庭环境中，金钱所承载的象征意义可能会导致冲突和剥削。一些家庭成员可能觉得有权拿走年长亲戚的钱，理由包括“无论如何我都会得到它”、“我已经赚到了”或“我更需要它”。<br><br>佩奇·乌尔里 (Page Ulrey) 是一名西雅图虐待老人案件检察官，我已经记录了她十多年的工作，她告诉我，她的大部分家庭剥削案件都是由赌博和购物成瘾助长的，比如两个姐妹在花光了母亲超过 85,000 美元的积蓄后承认盗窃罪，其中包括“在赌场赌博和狂买劣质的家庭购物网络珠宝”。朗告诉我，富国银行顾问发现的许多案例都涉及女儿，她们往往承担着年迈父母的大部分照顾工作。 “然后，如果妈妈说她甚至要把史蒂文的财产分给兄弟姐妹，女儿会想，<em>这不公平。我一直在做所有的工作</em>，”他说。 “这并不能证明剥削是正当的，但她说得有道理。”<br><br>关于哪些美国老年人最有可能成为受害者，还有很多事情需要了解，但数据表明，有色人种老年人比白人老年人损失更多。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/gerontologist/article/50/6/744/629839">一项研究</a>发现，23% 的老年非裔美国人遭受经济剥削，这一比例约为非非裔美国人的三倍。一项针对洛杉矶低收入拉丁裔的小型<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3396729/#:~:text=The%20promotores%20conducted%20door%2Dto,neglect%20within%20the%20previous%20year.">试点研究</a>发现，十分之四的人报告称自己是老年人忽视或虐待（包括经济剥削）的受害者。 （有色人种和受教育程度<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cuimc.columbia.edu/news/one-10-older-americans-has-dementia">较低</a>的人的痴呆症发病率略高。）<br><br>富人也不能幸免：纽约慈善家布鲁克·阿斯特的儿子因担任他患有认知障碍的母亲的授权书而给自己追溯了100万美元的“加薪”，被判犯有重大盗窃罪。但对于那些财力较少的人来说，损失通常更加不稳定。凯伦·威尔逊 (Keren Wilson) 是一位辅助生活先驱、老龄化专家、煤矿工人的女儿，几年前给我打电话，她对西弗吉尼亚州麦克道尔县的所见所闻感到困扰。她说，社会保障支票刚到，犯罪率就飙升，面临严重疼痛和临终关怀的老年人拒绝接受临终关怀服务，因为担心如果家里有止痛药的消息传出去，他们就会被抢劫。<br><br>尽管我们的社会已经建立了一些机制来解决这一复杂的社会问题，但它们还远远不够。与老龄化的许多其他方面一样，我们过分关注危机发生<em>后的</em>反应。 We&#39;ve done little to advance our understanding of what steps prevent the financial exploitation of older people.这个主题值得家庭和政策制定者更多地考虑和对话。<br><br>一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/elderjustice/prosecutors/statutes?field_statute_state=NY&amp;field_statute_category=All">州</a>将各种类型的剥削行为定为刑事犯罪，并认为某些老年受害者“容易受到伤害”，从而可以加重处罚。但我一直无法找到任何证据表明此类措施可以防止或减少经济损失。尽管有些案件值得起诉，但当家庭成员是被指控的犯罪者时，受害者可能不愿意寻求帮助，因为他们不希望亲人面临刑事处罚。美国联邦贸易委员会 (FTC) 和美国退休人员协会 (AARP) 等组织定期发布文章<em>，请留意这一内容！</em>有关新骗局的列表和指南。但这种消费者教育能防止多少损失也不清楚，特别是当目标人群有认知障碍时。此类警告也给潜在受害者留下了保护自己的负担。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/02/happiness-age-investment/622818/">亚瑟·C·布鲁克斯（Arthur C. Brooks）：带来晚年幸福的七个习惯</a><br><br>我们应该更多地关注撤离的驱动因素和手段，以及如何中断它们。 For example, credit and gift cards or reloadable cards (like a prepaid debit card) are used in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/protecting-older-consumers-2020-2021-report-federal-trade-commission/protecting-older-consumers-report-508.pdf">more than half</a> of scams involving older people, yet we have done little to make those cards less inviting instruments of theft. Wire and bank transfer frauds are used in fewer than 10 percent of fraud events, but they represent by far the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/reports/protecting-older-consumers-2020-2021-report-federal-trade-commission/protecting-older-consumers-report-508.pdf">largest</a> amount of money lost. Here, recent <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.finra.org/rules-guidance/rulebooks/finra-rules/2165">financial-industry</a> practices and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.investor.gov/senior-safe-act-fact-sheet">federal</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nasaa.org/industry-resources/senior-issues/model-act-to-protect-vulnerable-adults-from-financial-exploitation/">state</a> policy changes show promise. In 2018, the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA), <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.finra.org/rules-guidance/guidance/faqs/frequently-asked-questions-regarding-finra-rules-relating-financial-exploitation-seniors">mandated</a> that the broker-dealers it oversees adopt certain protections: allowing trained employees to temporarily freeze suspicious transactions and, if appropriate, investigate or report them, and inviting clients to authorize a “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.finra.org/investors/investing/investment-accounts/brokerage-accounts#trusted-contacts">trusted contact</a> ” for their accounts, someone a financial institution can reach out to with concerns. Researchers who tracked the rollout of these protections found that allowing brokers to freeze suspicious transactions reduced suspected fraud cases and personal bankruptcies by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w27225/w27225.pdf">about 5 percent</a> each. But bank regulators have not mandated such protections.<br><br> These and other preventive measures should be available to all Americans and easy to enroll in and use—as easy as signing up for direct deposit of paychecks or automatic retirement savings. That could mean creating a suite of protections that people can opt into when they enroll in Social Security, including access to free or inexpensive fraud-alert programs, financial management and planning assistance, and a trustworthy elder-friendly helpline.<br><br> The medical community should look for solutions too, such as finding ways to reduce risk. Duke Han, a neuropsychologist at the University of Southern California, is studying factors that might be related to older peoples&#39; susceptibility to exploitation, such as feeling financially insecure or being unfamiliar with cultural norms around what&#39;s expected when a stranger calls.<br><br> When my siblings and I cleaned out our father&#39;s apartment after he died at 93, we found dozens of cheap pens, trinkets, and notepads he had received from organizations encouraging him to keep his checks coming. Their solicitations kept coming too, long after he died. We were fortunate. But for many, the massive machinery to extract money from older Americans leads to tragedies that inflict pain long after the people targeted are gone.<br><br> <small><em>This article has been adapted from Connolly&#39;s book,</em> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-measure-of-our-age-navigating-care-safety-money-and-meaning-later-in-life-m-t-connolly/9781541702721">The Measure of Our Age: Navigating Care, Safety, Money, and Meaning Later in Life</a> <em>.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/elder-senior-citizen-scams-fraud-exploitation/674793/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/elder-senior-citizen-scams-fraud-exploitation/674793/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Germany Is No Longer Exceptional]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The country <span>is joining</span> the European mainstream, with its political class struggling to counter rising far-right support and an economy that is no longer best-in-class.<br> A <span class="smallcaps">sked what came</span> to her mind when thinking about Germany, former Chancellor Angela Merkel once <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rnd.de/politik/65-jahre-merkel-die-besten-zitate-der-kanzlerin-ESR56SZBAYROXOJXEX6BOVYQUA.html">said</a> , “I think of airtight windows. No other country can build as airtight and as beautiful windows.”<br><br> With its history tainted, post-1945 Germany looked to its economy for a positive conception of itself. The goods Germany produced, such as those quality windows, allowed politicians to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.destatis.de/DE/Methoden/WISTA-Wirtschaft-und-Statistik/2007/04/exportweltmeister-deutschland-042007.pdf?__blob=publicationFile">celebrate</a> the country as an “export world champion.” Germany Inc., was a well-oiled capitalist-corporatist ensemble. Trade-union leaders and CEOs strategized instead of shouting at one another, and the success of German industry offered an unsullied source of pride. So did the fiscal conservatism and hawkish monetary policy that allowed the Federal Republic to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/pdf/other/mb201005en_pp99-110en.pdf">master</a> high inflation in the 1970s and &#39;80s better than the rest of Europe and the United States were able to.<br><br> Economic success provided Germany not only with a postwar identity but also with the power of attraction. During the Cold War, the promise of a freer, better life in the Federal Republic prompted East Germans to flee the Communist German Democratic Republic. When they toppled the Berlin Wall in November 1989, East Berliners first <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.welt.de/politik/20-jahre-mauerfall/article5141880/Kollektives-Tagebuch-Donnerstag-9-November-89.html">stormed</a> Kurfürstendamm, the shopping street and temple of capitalism they had fantasized about but had never gotten to see. German leaders relied on the country&#39;s economic might to power reunification, co-build the European Union, and welcome Syrians escaping civil war in 2015.<br><br> Just three decades after reunification, per capita GDP in the former GDR<i> </i>is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/4187653/11571499/GDP_per_capita_ver3-01.jpg">higher</a> than in many regions in northern France. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://data.oecd.org/unemp/unemployment-rate.htm">Unemployment</a> , at 2.9 percent, is well below the US or EU average, even though Germany took in a million Syrians in 2015 and another million Ukrainians in 2022. Berlin remains the biggest financial contributor to the EU—the organization Paris initially designed to keep post–Nazi Germany in check but that has now made war between its 27 members close to unthinkable.<br><br> Yet an economy, even Germany&#39;s, is a slender thread on which to hang a national identity. When France struggles with unemployment, the French still have the revolutionary myth of 1789 and the Eiffel Tower. When Greece is on the brink of default, the Greeks still have Plato and olive trees. When the United States skirts another financial crisis, there is still the American dream and Beyoncé. But what happens in an “economy in search of a political <i>raison d&#39;être,</i> ” as the historian <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hsozkult.de/publicationreview/id/reb-6233">Werner Abelshauser</a> once described the postwar Federal Republic, if its GDP suddenly stops growing? We are about to find out.<br><br> Germany&#39;s economy is running out of steam, and not only because of COVID or because Russian President Vladimir Putin has turned off the gas tap. Together with—and perhaps because of—its economic malaise, the country is living through a political earthquake. Germany&#39;s wealth, its exemplary parliamentary democracy, and its big efforts to confront its Nazi history are no longer keeping nativist parties at bay.<br><br> Two years into the government of Chancellor Olaf Scholz, the far-right Alternative for Germany (AfD) is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wahlrecht.de/umfragen/">polling</a> as high as 20 percent. This July, the AfD got its first mayor <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20230703-german-far-right-party-afd-scores-another-electoral-victory">elected</a> with 51.1 percent of the votes in the town of Raguhn-Jeßnitz in the eastern state of Saxony-Anhalt.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/german-military-olaf-scholz-ukraine-russia-war/673224/">George E. Bogden: Germany&#39;s unkept promise</a><br><br> The AfD figurehead Alexander Gauland once <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/social-media-ap-top-news-middle-east-germany-international-news-35a927e3ae954fa386a9e2406ae4439a">said</a> that “Hitler and the Nazis are just a speck of bird poop in more than 1,000 years of successful German history.” The AfD <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.berliner-zeitung.de/politik-gesellschaft/krieg-afd-will-ukraine-politik-neu-verpacken-keine-plumpen-antiamerikanischen-reflexe-ein-positionspapier-soll-es-richten-kritik-an-parteichef-tino-chrupalla-li.333210">opposes</a> weapons deliveries to Ukraine and wants to terminate economic sanctions on Russia. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.spiegel.de/panorama/europawahlkampf-afd-will-nato-diskussion-meiden-a-8303038f-b6e5-4cd0-b8bc-84371de47a5b">Split</a> about whether Germany should leave NATO, the party agrees that all US troops should vacate the country and the Ramstein air base be shut down. The party also <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.afd.de/grundsatzprogramm/">wants</a> the country to stop using the Euro and dissolve the European Parliament.<br><br> “As the third-biggest contributor to the United Nations,” Germany should have a permanent seat on the Security Council, the AfD program states. The party denies that climate change is human-made, wants to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.afd.de/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/20210611_AfD_Programm_2021.pdf">make</a> abortions “an exception,” and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/innenpolitik/fluechtlingsgipfel-afd-100.html">wants to classify</a> Afghanistan as a “safe country,” meaning that asylum requests from Afghans would be only rarely granted. The AfD co-leader Tino Chrupalla also wants schools to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUISOT7oLXQ">teach</a> more German poems, even though, when asked, he is unable to name a single one.<br><br> A recent <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.insa-consulere.de/archivpotentialanalyse/">poll</a> shows that, notwithstanding this radical program, only 57 percent of Germans now say that they could never imagine voting for the AfD—almost the same percentage, incidentally, by which Emmanuel Macron <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/Elections/Les-resultats/Presidentielles/elecresult__presidentielle-2022/(path)/presidentielle-2022/FE.html">won</a> the second round of the French presidential election in 2022 against the nationalist Marine Le Pen.<br><br> We are living through the end of German exceptionalism. The country&#39;s economy is fragile, and the rise of the AfD makes its politics as unpredictable as those of Austria or Italy. In short, Germany is joining the European mainstream. And that means that trouble is ahead.<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">n late 2022,</span> Germany&#39;s economy entered a recession that lasted at least until spring 2023 and may yet continue. The longer-term picture is worse: The Federal Republic is the only big Euro member whose economy has not yet fully <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=12p4H">recovered</a> to pre-pandemic levels. In fact, German GDP has roughly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=12p4H">stagnated</a> since 2019. And German manufacturing is the main problem: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://think.ing.com/snaps/german-ip-april-070623/">Industrial output</a> lags pre-pandemic levels by some 5 percent.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2022/03/germany-putin-ukraine-invasion/623322/">Read: Europe&#39;s sleeping giant awakens</a><br><br> If you ask Berlin who is to blame, there seems to be just one answer: high energy prices sparked by Russia&#39;s war against Ukraine. The AfD and far-left Die Linke are nostalgic for cheap Russian gas, while the opposing center-right CDU and the governing pro-business FDP blame the Greens for insisting on turning off the country&#39;s last nuclear-power plants this spring. Scholz decided to turbocharge renewables investment, and no one in Berlin expects the government to advance the exit from coal energy from 2030 to 2038, as initially planned.<br><br> But high energy prices are not the only drag on the economy, nor are they new. German electricity prices have run significantly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://strom-report.com/strompreise-europa/">above</a> the European average for at least a decade, and Russian gas was never really cheap, especially if you compare it with US fracking gas.<br><br> The reason Germany ceased to be Europe&#39;s growth engine has less to do with Russian energy than with changing circumstances in the export markets where the country&#39;s industrial champions once flourished. In the 2000s, former Chancellor Gerhard Schröder slashed unemployment benefits and created a low-wage sector to help German exporters increase their market shares across Europe. Since then, many other European countries, including France and Italy, have made reforms to cut labor costs themselves, and Germany faces tougher competition in its biggest export market and has been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?oldid=452727#Evolution_of_intra-EU_trade_in_goods">running a trade deficit in goods</a> with other EU members since 2020.<br><br> Outside the EU, “made in Germany” goods struggle to find new clients. Exports to China have been roughly <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Brad_Setser/status/1586421747934531585?s=20">flat</a> since mid-2015 and may even start to drop, as President Xi Jinping has made clear that he wants to make his country less dependent on European industry. German car exports to China were <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.destatis.de/EN/Press/2023/05/PE23_182_51.html">down</a> 24 percent in the first three months of 2023 compared with the same period in 2022. The US is Germany&#39;s second-largest market after the EU, accounting for <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://santandertrade.com/en/portal/analyse-markets/germany/foreign-trade-in-figures">8.9</a> percent of its exports, but to top off Germany&#39;s troubles, Washington is becoming more protectionist under Joe Biden. The Inflation Reduction Act, for instance, includes purchase subsidies for electric vehicles that primarily benefit buyers of cars produced in North America.<br><br> So what can Berlin do if exports won&#39;t be driving German growth anymore?<br><br> The obvious solution is for Germany to spend more. Greater investment could raise productivity in a country where <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reisereporter.de/reisenews/deutsche-bahn-ist-im-europa-vergleich-am-unpuenktlichsten-3FRLA33QE6JC5ITOS6Z3JBC3X5.html">the railways</a> have the worst delays among major European countries and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smartdroid.de/im-eu-vergleich-landen-deutsche-handynetze-weit-hinten/">cellphone</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://de.statista.com/statistik/daten/studie/224924/umfrage/internet-verbindungsgeschwindigkeit-in-ausgewaehlten-weltweiten-laendern/">internet connectivity</a> are underfunded and therefore <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://de.statista.com/statistik/daten/studie/224924/umfrage/internet-verbindungsgeschwindigkeit-in-ausgewaehlten-weltweiten-laendern/">patchy</a> . Investment could boost demand, and liberalizing policies could rebalance the economy toward services. But a dogma of balanced budgets and debt avoidance remains deeply anchored among German politicians and voters.<br><br> Germans don&#39;t seem to feel much urgency around these questions at the moment. Unemployment is still low. In Mannheim, students are out and about, enjoying spaghetti ice cream, the local speciality, priced at €5.80, while the once slightly rundown Berlin Ku&#39;damm feels more and more like the manicured Avenue Montaigne in Paris. In March this year, Chancellor Scholz even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.t-online.de/nachrichten/deutschland/innenpolitik/id_100141426/olaf-scholz-rechnet-neuem-wirtschaftswunder-in-deutschland.html">said</a> the country will soon see a new “ <i>Wirtschaftswunder</i> ”—Germany&#39;s age of postwar growth—a prediction that should leave any economist gasping.<br><br> In short, the penny has not yet dropped. Germany&#39;s political elite hasn&#39;t been moved to take the risky step of running up debts and liberalizing at the same time. But until it does, the country&#39;s economy will likely lag European growth. And if the economy ceases to serve as a source of national pride, political forces may thrive by brandishing more nativist concepts of German identity.<br><br> M <span class="smallcaps">ore and more</span> governments across Europe are led by right-wing parties: in Italy, Sweden, Finland, and soon possibly Spain. In all of these countries, the center-right no longer has qualms about working with the far-right. Now Germany, whose effort to confront its Nazi history seemed to inoculate its politicians from having to deal with a large far-right party, is also falling prey to populism and nationalism.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2021/09/germany-election-afd-far-right/620114/">Read: What Germany says about far-right politics</a><br><br> The AfD&#39;s rise to 20 percent in the polls—twice what it commanded in the 2021 parliamentary elections—has many causes. The party&#39;s bastion is the formerly Communist east, where authoritarian attitudes and resentment of traditional parties <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/1467-923X.12859">feed</a> off of feelings of having been the losers in Germany&#39;s reunification. But something broader is going on. For Germans, the hallmark of good government is “ <i>Ruhe und Ordnung</i> ,” calm and order. The three parties in Scholz&#39;s ruling coalition—the center-left SPD, the Greens, and the pro-business FDP—squabble over everything, including whether to ban gas heating systems, how to deal with China, and whether to raise the child-benefits system. The result is neither calm nor order, at a time when inflation and the energy crisis are already destabilizing life in Germany.<br><br> The party has also benefited from a backlash against Germany&#39;s progressive agenda on climate and migration. Despite the country&#39;s reputation abroad as a climate champion, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/may/02/many-europeans-want-climate-action-but-less-so-if-it-changes-their-lifestyle-shows-poll">in a poll of seven European countries</a> , Germans were the least willing among Europeans to switch to electric cars, cut meat consumption, or spend out of their own pockets to renovate their houses to save the climate.<br><br> As for migration, racist views are ingrained in Germany&#39;s formerly Communist east, where more than 28 percent of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/politik/starke-partei/">survey</a> respondents agreed that “Jews have something special and idiosyncratic” and “don&#39;t really fit with us,” and roughly 20 percent said that the crimes of the Nazi regime had been grossly exaggerated. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dw.com/en/half-of-eastern-germans-want-authoritarian-rule/a-66068519#:~:text=Islamophobia%2C%20antisemitism%20and%20xenophobia%20are,a%20%22strong%20party%22%20leadership.">Half</a> of those surveyed wanted a ban on Muslim immigration. But the AfD has also been able to mobilize an anti-immigration electorate in big, rich, formerly West German states, such as Bavaria, the land of Siemens and <i>Weisswurst</i> , and Baden-Württemberg, home to Mercedes and <i>Spätzle</i> .<br><br> Economic conditions as well as refugee crises likely have something to do with the rightward shift on this issue. In the late 1960s, when West Germany hit its first postwar economic recession and migrants from Southern Europe and Turkey started working in its factories, the neo-Nazi NPD won <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tagesschau.de/wahl/archiv/1968-04-28-LT-DE-BW/index.shtml">9.8 percent</a> in Baden-Württemberg and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tagesschau.de/wahl/archiv/1966-11-20-LT-DE-BY/index.shtml">7.4 percent</a> in Bavaria. In the 1990s, when Germany struggled with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://de.statista.com/statistik/daten/studie/1127090/umfrage/arbeitslosenquote-der-bundesrepublik-deutschland/">high</a> unemployment and refugees came from the former Yugoslavia, the far-right <i>Republikaner</i> easily <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tagesschau.de/wahl/archiv/1992-04-05-LT-DE-BW/index.shtml">won</a> 10.9 percent in elections in Baden-Württemberg. Both parties vanished into irrelevance when the center-right CDU shifted its migration policy to the right.<br><br> The eastern states of Thuringia and Saxony will hold elections next year—national elections will follow in 2025—and the CDU will need to decide whether it will continue marginalizing the far-right or start working with it instead. The AfD is leading the polls in Thuringia and polling a strong second in Saxony. The national leader of the CDU, Friedrich Merz, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/germany-conservatives-cdu-merz-migrants-b049e245559f85c318d3f1104bcfb3ab">says</a> he will not work with the AfD, but in Berlin many fear that the local CDU branches in Thuringia and Saxony may decide to do it anyway. Merz cannot prevent this if he does not want to risk splitting the party in two.<br><br> G <span class="smallcaps">ermany is joining</span> the European mainstream, with its political class struggling to counter rising far-right support and an economy that is no longer best-in-class. The two things that made postwar Germany unique in Europe are no more. Even Germany&#39;s football team, second only to the economy as a source of post-1945 national pride, is not what it used to be.<br><br> Germany&#39;s <i>déclassement</i> is a problem for the country itself, but also for the EU. When the bloc&#39;s ancestor, the European Coal and Steel Community, came into being in the 1950s, its raison d&#39;être was to domesticate Germany and stabilize the continent with it. Later, the EU started to rely on Germany as its anchor. The German economy was strong enough to help finance the European project, and its politicians were often far-sighted enough to realize that advancing the EU was in Berlin&#39;s interest.<br><br> Now the rise of the AfD is pushing Berlin to become an unreliable partner in Europe. The CDU was once the champion of Schengen, the EU&#39;s policy to allow for passport-less travel across the continent. The party&#39;s leader, Merz, clearly concerned about covering his right flank, has now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.berliner-zeitung.de/news/steigende-fluechtlingszahlen-friedrich-merz-fuer-erneute-grenzkontrollen-in-der-eu-li.331394">called</a> for reintroducing passport checks at Germany&#39;s borders with other EU members, such as Czechia, in order to turn away migrants.<br><br> The Scholz government surprised Brussels by torpedoing at the very last minute a decision to ban the sale of combustion-engine cars in Europe as of 2035. The FDP, which was the main force behind this decision, received a much-needed boost in the polls as a result. As the AfD criticizes the “reckless” spending of the Scholz government, the FDP and the chancellor are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-05-23/scholz-plots-20-billion-of-german-budget-cuts-in-snub-to-greens?sref=ojq9DljU">doubling down</a> on spending cuts. Germany is becoming less willing to spend for itself and the EU.<br><br> For a decade, pundits speculated that France, led by Le Pen, would put the European project to its biggest stress test. But instead the German speed car seems ready to cut across France to the chase.<br><br> The AfD may one day accede to national government, but it cannot do so on its own. To work in a coalition, the party will almost certainly have to compromise on its most radical policy propositions, such as closing the US military base in Ramstein. But even with the AfD merely exerting pressure on German politics, the EU must sooner or later face an adjustment—to a future in which Germany is no longer an economic and political anchor so much as a source of instability.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/germany-national-identity-afd-party-political-instability/674786/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/germany-national-identity-afd-party-political-instability/674786/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[What 'Barbie' Knows About Real-Life Women]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这不是芭比本人。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/E-8HjG745jbDDrxrxTt410CMlo4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/barbie_hr/original.jpg" alt="玛格特·罗比和亚美莉卡·费雷拉在《芭比娃娃》中" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>华纳兄弟影业公司</figcaption></figure><strong><em>本文包含电影</em></strong><strong>《芭比娃娃》的剧透。</strong><br><br>格蕾塔·葛韦格执导的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/"><em>《芭比》</em></a>就像芭比超级粉丝的想象力一样。娃娃们有精心编排的舞蹈。对话充满轻松，了解美泰产品的乐趣。几乎每个场景——尤其是芭比乐园中的场景，这个由不同真人大小的芭比娃娃和他们各自喜爱的肯斯经营的塑料世界——都包含创意布景、对做作电影的厚颜无耻的参考，以及最粉红色的服装。<br><br>一个正常的成年人可能会觉得与这样一个阳光普照、闪闪发光的幻想世界格格不入，但格洛丽亚（亚美莉卡·费雷拉饰）不仅仅是游客：她是一个在还是个小女孩的时候就花了很多时间和芭比娃娃（玛格特·罗比饰）玩耍的女人。现在，作为一个成年人，格洛丽亚一直在尝试与十几岁的女儿建立联系，但未能成功。在悲伤中，她重新审视了她的安慰玩具，不小心将她最黑暗的想法灌输给了娃娃，导致芭比娃娃“失灵”——她的弓形脚变平了，她开始思考死亡。当格洛丽亚通过一系列神奇事件遇见了芭比娃娃时，她成为了芭比娃娃的向导，让她了解自己超越玩具的能力，同时也是理解这部电影的关键，通过精彩的独白将影片中的许多想法集中起来。<br><br>格洛丽亚的演讲是在她和芭比的角色互换的时刻进行的。在现实世界中，芭比（被称为“刻板芭比”，以将她与其他变体区分开来）发现，女性实际上并不能掌控现存的一切。当她回到芭比乐园时，她的焦虑加深了，肯一家在了解了人类男人的行为方式后，确立了父权制的观念——肯一家管理政府！芭比娃娃给他们带来啤酒！到处都是马用具！——芭比除了成为她的肯（瑞恩·高斯林饰）在她自己所谓的天堂里的装饰品之外别无他用。为了回应芭比的生存危机，格洛丽亚对她进行了一番鼓舞人心的演讲，逐字逐句地转变为对作为一个女人所带来的不可能的期望进行尖锐而富有同情心的剖析。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-review-greta-gerwig/674742/">阅读：芭比娃娃怎么了？</a><br><br> “不知何故，我们总是做错事，”她开始说道，然后举出了一长串例子。女性要瘦，但不能太瘦；争取领导角色，但不要过于激进；热爱做母亲，但不要把做母亲当作唯一的工作；承认性别不平等的存在，但不抱怨。 “你必须永远不会变老，永远不会粗鲁，永远不会炫耀，永远不会自私，永远不会跌倒，永远不会失败，永远不会表现出恐惧，永远不会越界，”格洛丽亚解释道。 “太难了;这太矛盾了……我只是厌倦了看着自己和其他女人把自己绑在一起，这样人们才会喜欢我们。如果这一切对于一个仅仅代表女性的娃娃来说也是如此，那我什至不知道。”<br><br>这是一部典型的葛韦格式的独白，继承了编剧兼导演改编的<em>《小妇人</em>》中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0D8nRpJsQlk&amp;ab_channel=Movieclips">对婚姻的坦率分析</a>， <em>《伯德小姐》</em>中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BVzFS1M_-rM&amp;ab_channel=Methition">对亲子关系的紧张反思</a>，以及<em>《弗朗西斯·哈》</em>中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=94rtEPIifpc&amp;ab_channel=MrNautica">对最好友谊的由衷评价</a>（她与搭档诺亚·鲍姆巴赫合写了<em>《芭比娃娃》</em> ）。和那些演讲一样，格洛丽亚的演讲有点漫无目的，有点难为情，有点愤慨，但费雷拉的表演却非常认真，带着恰到好处的愤怒。格洛丽亚所说的大部分内容对于观看这部电影的成年女性来说可能是显而易见的，但她朴实无华、实事求是的表达方式因其原始性而令人耳目一新。独白以一种听天由命且相当不满意的语气结束，这只会让它变得更加强大。场景随着每一句话而构建，格洛丽亚似乎准备概述一个值得 TED 演讲的解决方案——但不存在。<br><br>毕竟，无论是在现实世界还是在芭比乐园中，都没有一个完美的解决方案可以让女性的生活不再痛苦。独白之所以如此成功，是因为它有助于表明，即使是糖果覆盖的广阔空间也不是理想的：格洛丽亚谈到的压力影响着每一个梦想屋的居住者，通常以更肤浅的方式。例如，芭比娃娃看到典型的芭比娃娃的扁平足时感到震惊；当其中一个人未能达到社会的主观审美标准时，其他人就会像真正的人类一样迅速做出判断。随着影片的展开，明智地需要时间来观察芭比乐园并不是一个平等的堡垒，至少当肯斯作为无权无势的公民生活时，他们唯一的角色就是被芭比娃娃注意到。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">阅读：芭比真的能拥有这一切吗？</a><br><br>对于一部像《芭比<em>娃娃》</em>这样荒诞而华丽的电影来说，格洛丽亚阴郁的独白是一个冒险的节奏，但它至关重要地提醒人们，这部电影到底存在的原因，以及为什么它可以超越<em>巴本</em>海默模因和几乎势不可挡的营销活动。影片指出，芭比娃娃——一个玩具、一个偶像——自 1959 年首次亮相以来，一直是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/05/tiny-shoulders-review-hulu/559277/">看似无休无止的争论</a>的主题，因为正如格洛丽亚明确指出的那样，作为一名女性意味着成为关于美丽标准和性别角色的看似无休止的辩论的主题。近年来，娃娃系列<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/barbies-hips-dont-lie/432741/">增加了多种肤色和体型</a>，使品牌现代化，但芭比娃娃拱形脚的形象经久不衰是有原因的：芭比娃娃必须始终保持踮起脚尖，走一条优雅的、不可能的路线，才能向女孩们塑造女性气质。<br><br>产品是我们自我形象的反映，而自我形象反过来又受到我们购买的产品的影响，创造出一个永无休止的循环，这种想法令人兴奋，而且可能会在观看这部电影的孩子们身上引起共鸣。在我的放映过程中，一个离我几个座位的小女孩一遍又一遍地问她妈妈解释格洛丽亚在说什么。 “<em>什么啊？</em> ”她在独白中低声说道，然后在演讲结束时重复了这个问题，听起来比之前更加困惑。她的困惑让我笑了——然后又让我感到沮丧，只是一点点。我想，<em>总有一天</em>，<em>她会明白的</em>。如果幸运的话，也许她身边会有一个人——芭比娃娃、格洛丽亚——让她知道她并不孤单。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 13:39:24 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/barbie-movie-america-ferrera/674781/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Colson Whitehead Loses the Plot]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>《骗子宣言》的</em>动力和限制都在于其最吸引人的特征：作者的声音。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/ZaQAoIW56Nz2130Aaz5Utqa69cU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/genre_fiction_2/original.jpg" alt="纽约照片上的黄色迷宫" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图由 Joanne Imperio/《大西洋月刊》拍摄。资料来源：Allan Tannenbaum / Getty；安东尼·巴博萨/盖蒂；贝特曼/盖蒂；唐纳森收藏/盖蒂；沃尔特·莱波拉蒂/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>在过去的三年里，我在乔治城大学教授创意写作课程，在那段时间里，我开始接受一些我最初觉得奇怪的事情：我的大多数学生更喜欢阅读和写作类型小说——科幻小说、悬疑小说、浪漫小说——而不是文学小说。 （对差异的粗略解释是：文学小说通常类似于现实生活并关注人物，而类型小说往往依赖于熟悉的主题并优先考虑情节。）我最初构建了一个包含各种经典和当代文学短篇小说的教学大纲，但我很快了解到我的学生热衷于创作类似于他们在课外所消费的作品：奇幻史诗、世界末日科幻故事、无畏和下流的浪漫故事。<br><br>我绝不能免受科幻和奇幻小说的魅力的影响，尽管我长期以来更喜欢阅读文学小说，因为它普遍致力于探索人类为何以我们的方式行事和思考。但我的学生热情地谈论了为什么他们发现自己最喜欢的故事如此吸引人：他们声称这些作品为他们的超强情感提供了坚固的容器，这些情感远远超出了我所分配的作品的现实主义范围。他们还认为，类型小说更适合捕捉当前时刻的高度不现实，因为它有丰富的新闻和信息，通常感觉像是日常的情节曲折。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/09/romance-novels-women-elinor-glyn-books/670609/">阅读：不要称他们为垃圾</a><br><br>我开始寻找一座桥梁，寻找一位善于将流派元素融入写作，同时又能保持优秀文学作品所要求的工艺品质的艺术家。我立刻想到了科尔森·怀特海德。自他的职业生涯开始以来，怀特海就以他强有力的处女作<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-intuitionist-colson-whitehead/9780385493000?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《直觉主义者》</em></a>开始，出色地实现了这种模式的融合。但同时使用这两个音域并非没有陷阱，我的学生也可以从怀特海那里学到这一课。他的最新小说<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/crook-manifesto-colson-whitehead/9780385545150?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《克鲁克宣言》</em></a>展示了他以多种风格熟练写作的非凡能力、他的语言技巧以及他惯常的尖锐而广泛的句子。然而这部小说并没有达到他在之前作品中所取得的成就。它的人物感觉并不完全充实，它的情节也没有捕捉到读者可能从犯罪小说中所期待的极端感受和情况。因为这些元素并没有完全融合在一起，所以这本书既受到其最吸引人的特征的推动，又受到限制：怀特海的声音。<br><br>类型小说的功能有点像流行的烹饪菜肴：通常有两条成功之路。首先是精确而巧妙地遵循食谱，这样当有人尝到你的胡萝卜蛋糕时，毫无疑问你已经提供了珍贵美味的纯正版本。第二条路是脱离食谱，以一种同时引用和提升菜肴的方式重新发明菜肴。怀特海德在他的职业生涯中通过第二种方法取得了成功。例如，在他的第一个普利策奖得主<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-underground-railroad-colson-whitehead/9780345804327?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《地下铁路》</em></a>中，他将庇护逃亡奴隶的名义上的好撒玛利亚人网络转变为实际的火车站网络。他巧妙地将流派和文学成分结合起来——这里有一个推进性的、流浪汉式的情节，也充满了令人痛苦的真实人物——他挑战并扰乱了许多读者认为他们知道的历史。<br><br> <em>《骗子宣言》</em>是怀特海德之前的小说<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/harlem-shuffle-colson-whitehead/9780525567271?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>《哈莱姆洗牌》</em></a>的续集，该小说讲述了一个名叫雷·卡尼的男子的犯罪故事，他靠获取赃物并出售它们来获取利润。 <em>《骗子宣言》</em>也以卡尼为中心，但在这部小说中，我们已经前进了几年，他最近从非法活动中退休，专注于经营他在哈莱姆区蓬勃发展的家具店。背景是 20 世纪 70 年代衰落的纽约市，正如怀特海德所说，“如果上东区也开始变得像垃圾一样，你就知道这座城市将会走向地狱。”卡尼十几岁的女儿梅渴望参加杰克逊五兄弟即将在麦迪逊广场花园举行的音乐会。由于无法通过传统方式获得门票，卡尼决定参与最后一项非法计划来获得门票。事情变得一团糟，他很快发现自己卷入了一场令人痛苦的犯罪狂潮中。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/10/colson-whitehead-harlem-shuffle/619821/">阅读：建立在其基础上的国家的犯罪是什么？</a><br><br>小说的麻烦从第二部分开始，发生在几年后，主要涉及一个名叫Zippo的角色试图在哈莱姆区拍摄一部黑人剥削影片（卡尼的商店作为其中一个场景的布景）。卡尼现在已经是一个小人物了，怀特海在前一节中建立的叙事线索也大多被放弃了；结果， <em>《克鲁克宣言》</em>读起来不再像一本小说，而更像是一部看似相关的轶事选集。这一发展吸引了更多人对第三人称叙述者的关注，第三人称叙述者占据了巨大的存在。故事就这样消退了；叙述者成为本书各部分之间唯一有意义的联系。怀特海的闲聊散文可靠地吸引着读者，有时推进情节，有时似乎以其自身的流畅性和令人惊叹的精湛技艺而被吸引。这对于一部小说来说是一个福音，在这部小说中，确定我们为什么要踏上这段旅程变得越来越困难。<br><br>怀特海德继续写出一些业内最好的句子。他们博学而又平凡，充满了复杂的节奏感，并闪耀着魅力。例如，他在这里描述了 Zippo 作为纽约崭露头角的艺术家的经历：<br><br><p>像许多艺术家一样，Zippo 在他年轻的时候也缺乏关注，像许多艺术家一样，他将一点点赞美转化为蔑视观众的阶段：无敌！他开始打扮得像黑人萨尔瓦多·达利，还留着八字胡。他穿着丝绒步履蹒跚，推着婴儿车里的西瓜沿着迪卡尔布大道骚扰陌生人，询问他们是否“喜欢他的宝贝智利”。每个人都认为他大部分时间都处于兴奋状态。他不是。</p>有时，怀特海的句子会佯装朝一个方向发展，然后突然到达一个意想不到的目的地。几页后，当 Zippo 发现自己身处洛杉矶时，他写道：<br><br><p>洛杉矶的圣诞节是一件令人迷失方向的事情：圣诞老人穿着短裤，车间里的小精灵是过去的黄金插页和未来的女服务员#2。这座城市就像一部安东尼奥尼的电影。当你第一次看到它时，它很糟糕，然后你第二次看到它时，它是令人难以置信的。就这样，除了第二次还是很糟糕。</p>这些段落是全书所提供的语言乐趣的典型。然而，随着小说的继续，在不同的视角之间闪烁，语言以牺牲情节为代价来吸引人们的注意力。成为明星的是怀特海，而不是本书中各种色彩斑斓的人物。<br><br>早些时候，怀特海引入了几个似乎暗示特定类型故事的比喻。我们有改过自新的亡命之徒，不情愿地重新进入犯罪世界，有忠诚但无知的妻子，有在法律两侧工作的腐败警察，等等。但怀特海并没有利用这些元素来营造动力，而是在它们之上叠加了文学烟火：他雄心勃勃、复杂的句子；看似随机的观点转变；每当他的故事似乎正在逐渐成熟时，他就会频繁地插入冗长的描述；而且——或许最令人不安的是——阻碍小说连贯的叙事结构。<br><br>尽管他没有掌握正确的食谱，但阅读这本书的理由有很多。怀特海充满活力地描写了纽约，小说中充满了关于迪斯科十年期间非裔美国人在这座城市生活的引人入胜的社会评论。然而，当我阅读时，我无法停止思考我与学生的对话。我突然想到他们正在提出一个简单而革命性的想法——类型小说比文学小说更能反映现实生活。我相信这两种文学都能提供令人振奋的现实观点。当然，关键是故事的执行得如何。有时候，我们的生活似乎是由未经我们允许的情节所支配的；其他时候，我们从对自己和生活在我们生活中的人物的洞察中获得安慰和意义。最好的小说至少强调了其中一个——有时也强调了两者——这些现实。不幸的是， <em>《骗子宣言》</em>并没有满足这两个任务。我从阅读中学到了很多东西，但感觉从来都不是很真实。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 13:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/colson-whitehead-crook-manifesto-book-review/674775/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/colson-whitehead-crook-manifesto-book-review/674775/</item></channel></rss>